2.1.2 Redirect the script file to the stdin of the GNU APL interpreter
----------------------------------------------------------------------

Another method to execute an APL script file, say SCRIPT.apl, is to use
the input redirection of the shall:

     $ apl < SCRIPT.apl   # input redirection of SCRIPT.apl to stdin of apl

   Alternatively, the GNU APL command line option -f or -s can be used:

     $ apl -f SCRIPT.apl
     $ apl -s SCRIPT.apl

   Both ways of redirecting the file are almost identical; in the first
case redirection was performed by the shell running apl, while in the
second case the redirecting of the file was performed by apl itself.


File: apl.info,  Node: Make the script file executable,  Next: Starting GNU APL Scripts: a Conclusion,  Prev: Redirect the script file to the stdin of the GNU APL interpreter,  Up: APL Scripting

2.1.3 Make the script file executable
-------------------------------------

Alternatively the script can be made executable, specifying apl as its
interpreter (see also тАШ'man 2 execve'тАЩ).  For this to work, the first
line of the script must have a special format:

         #!/usr/bin/env apl --script

   тАШ--scriptтАЩ prevents: printing of a welcome banner, echoing of stdin
to stdout, automatic loading of a )CONTINUE workspace, and prevents
starting a thread for shared variable communication.

   If the path to the interpreter is relative (which might be useful if
you do not know in advance where the APL interpreter will be installed)
then it must be in $PATH of the shell that runs the script.


