2.1.6.1 тОХARG
............

The system variable тОХARG contains all command line arguments passed to
the interpreter.  In the initial example above this would be a nested
3-element vector:

         /usr/local/bin/apl --id 1010


File: apl.info,  Node: тОХENV,  Next: тОХINP,  Prev: тОХARG,  Up: Helpful Features for Scripting

2.1.6.2 тОХENV
............

There are usually at least two ways of passing parameters to a script:

   тАв as command line options, and/or
   тАв by means of environment variables

   Just as the system variable тОХARG makes the command line options used
available to APL, so does the system function тОХENV make the environment
variables available to APL. Since there normally exist far more
environment variables than command line options, тОХENV is a monadic
function whose argument is a filter for the name(s) of the variable(s)
to be retrieved.

   тОХENV B returns all environment variables whose name starts with B. If
тН┤B is 0, like:

           тОХENV ''

   then all environment variables of the process running GNU APL are
returned.

   The result of тОХENV is a (possibly empty) N├Ч2 matrix.  The first
column contains the name(s) of the environment variable(s), while the
second column contains their value(s).  The name and the value are both
strings.

   The number N of environment variables returned by тОХENV obviously
depends on the number of environment variables whose name begins with
the prefix given in B; shorter prefixes B therefore result in higher
counts N. B is case sensitive; by convention the names of environment
variables are all uppercase.  Note the subtle difference between shell
variables and environment variables in shells like bash: тОХENV returns
only environment variables (which are set with command setenv in bash),
but not shell variables (which are set with command set in bash).  For a
shell variable to occur in тОХENV it must be exported into the environment
of the process before the GNU APL interpreter is started.


File: apl.info,  Node: тОХINP,  Prev: тОХENV,  Up: Helpful Features for Scripting

2.1.6.3 тОХINP
............

If you need to create a longer static text, like the body of a web page,
then you would normally construct it in APL like this:

           BODY тЖР тКВ 'First line'
           BODY тЖР BODY , тКВ 'Second line'
           BODY тЖР BODY , тКВ 'Third line'
        ...

   The above is obviously not very handy for longer texts.  Instead you
may write the following in a GNU APL script:

           BODYтЖРтОХINP 'END-OF-тОХINP'
     First line
     Second line
     Third line
        ...
     END-OF-тОХINP

   This works like "Here documents" in bash.  The right argument of тОХINP
is the end of text marker.

   тОХINP also has a dyadic form where the left argument specifies an
escape sequence from text to APL and back to the text, similar to PHP
scripts.  For example:

           ZтЖР'<?apl' '?>' тОХINP 'END-OF-тОХINP'
     First line
     Time is now: <?apl тНХтОХTS ?>
     Third line
     ...
     END-OF-тОХINP

   This creates a mainly static text with a small dynamic plug-in
computed by APL:

           тКГZ
     First line
     Time is now: 2022 8 4 15 15 2 177
     Third line
     ...

   It should be noted that, while тОХINP simplifies the construction of
multi-line strings compared to standard APL, it has come of age and
these days an even simpler feature - Multi-line strings as described
below - is provided for the same purpose.  The monadic тОХINP has
therefore become obsolete.


