2.1.10 Automatic )MORE
----------------------

The GNU APL command )MORE provides, in some cases, additional
information about a prior APL error.  The availability of such
additional information is indicated by a + at the end of the error
message.  The additional information is automatically discarded when the
next non-empty line is entered.  For example:

           "ABC"[4]
     INDEX ERROR+
           'ABC'[4]
           ^    ^
           )MORE
     min index=тОХIO (=1), offending index=4, max index=тОХIO+2 (=3)
           тЧК тНЭ clears )MORE

           )MORE
     NO )MORE ERROR INFO

   This is rather useful in purely interactive mode where the user can
issue the )MORE command directly after an APL error has occurred to help
figure out what exactly went wrong.  In a script, however, the standard
)MORE command (as inherited from IBM APL2) is fairly useless for two
reasons:

   тАв A human user has a chance to issue the )MORE command interactively
     after an error has occurred, while a script continues after
     displaying the error message, and
   тАв It is rather difficult to predict where the next errors will occur,
     i.e.  where to place the )MORE command in the script.

   To make the )MORE command more useful for scripts, in GNU APL it can
be augmented with an optional argument AUTO like this:

           )MORE AUTO ON
     Automatic )MORE is now: ON

           "ABC"[4]
     min index=тОХIO (=1), offending index=4, max index=тОХIO+2 (=3)
     INDEX ERROR+
           'ABC'[4]
           ^    ^

   If ON/OFF is omitted then the automatic )MORE mode is toggled.  The
additional )MORE information is displayed before the standard 3-line APL
error message.


File: apl.info,  Node: Script Example,  Prev: Automatic )MORE,  Up: APL Scripting

2.1.11 Script Example
---------------------

Note that the two different ways of running an APL script have an impact
on how тОХARG looks like.  If stdin is redirected then there is only one
(possibly empty) set of command line options.  Otherwise there are two
sets of command line options: command line options for the apl
interpreter and command line options for the script.

   Consider the following simple script called SCRIPT.apl in directory
workspaces:

     #! /usr/local/bin/apl --script

     тКГтОХARG   тНЭ show command line options
     )OFF    тНЭ leave the interpreter

   If SCRIPT.apl is redirected to stdin of the APL interpreter:

      /usr/local/bin/apl --silent <  ../workspaces/SCRIPT.apl

      or

      /usr/local/bin/apl --silent -f ../workspaces/SCRIPT.apl

   then the first line тАШ#! /usr/local/bin/apl --scriptтАЩ of file
SCRIPT.apl is merely a comment (GNU APL accepts both the traditional APL
character тНЭ and the character # as start of a comment).  The тАШ-scriptтАЩ
option is therefore ignored and the following mix of input and output is
shown on the screen.  The input from the script is indented by the usual
APL prompt of 6 blanks, while the output of the APL interpreter is not
indented.

           #! /usr/local/bin/apl --script

           тКГтОХARG     тНЭ show command line options
           )OFF      тНЭ leave the interpreter

   If we run the same script directly:

     ../workspaces/SCRIPT.apl

   Then we get:

      /usr/local/bin/apl --script ../workspaces/SCRIPT.apl

   The тАШ-scriptтАЩ implies тАШ-noCINтАЩ so that the input lines for the
interpreter are no longer echoed to the output.  This is most likely
what you want when writing a script.

   Also, the first line of the script is no longer ignored as a comment,
but controls the command line argument (and thus тОХARG) of the
interpreter.  The additional command line argument
тАШ../workspaces/SCRIPT.aplтАЩ comes from function execve (see тАЩman 2
execveтАЩ).

   If we provide an argument, say SCRIPTARG, to SCRIPT.apl:

     ../workspaces/SCRIPT.apl SCRIPTARG

   then it shows up at the end of тОХARG:

      /usr/local/bin/apl --script ../workspaces/SCRIPT.apl SCRIPTARG

   A final note on scripting in GNU APL is that the тИЗ-editor works
slightly differently when it is used in a script.  If a user edits an
APL function interactively then an attempt to open an existing function
with a full header gives a DEFN ERROR:

           тИЗZтЖРFOO B
     [1] тИЗ

           тИЗZтЖРFOO B
     DEFN ERROR+
           тИЗZтЖРFOO B
                  ^
           )MORE
     attempt to тИЗ-open existing function with new function header

   In contrast to a user who can react to the DEFN ERROR, a script
cannot detect this situation and would continue to push lines (which
were intended to be the body of the defined function) into the APL
interpreter.  That would most likely cause fairly undesirable behavior.
For example, if the lines of a defined function start with line numbers
(like [1], [2], ...)  then every such line would give a SYNTAX ERROR,
and other errors can be expected as well.

   For that reason, if the тИЗ-editor is used in a script and attempts to
redefine an existing defined function then the existing function is
simply overwritten with the new one and no DEFN ERROR is raised.


File: apl.info,  Node: Axis argument in defined functions,  Next: Function Groups,  Prev: APL Scripting,  Up: Non-standard GNU APL Features

2.2 Axis argument in defined functions
======================================

Defined functions and operators (including lambdas) accept an axis
argument.  For example:

     тИЗZтЖРAverage[X] B
      ZтЖР(+/[X]B) ├╖ (тН┤B)[X]
     тИЗ

           Average[1] 5 5тН┤тН│25
     11 12 13 14 15

           Average[2] 5 5тН┤тН│25
     3 8 13 18 23

   Syntactically, the axis is used in the same way as for primitive
functions and operators.

   There are no constraints on the axis such as being integers.
Therefore you can use an axis as a third function argument.  Keep in
mind, however, that doing so will make your APL code incompatible with
other APL interpreters.  Use this feature carefully!


File: apl.info,  Node: Function Groups,  Next: Colored Output,  Prev: Axis argument in defined functions,  Up: Non-standard GNU APL Features

2.3 Function Groups
===================

In the old APL1 every function of the interpreter was represented by a
single APL character.  More precisely, the character represented 1, 2,
or 3 sub-functions and the sub-function was selected by the number of
arguments provided:

   тАв 1 for monadic functions,
   тАв 2 or monadic functions with axis,
   тАв 2 for dyadic functions (w/o axis), or
   тАв 3 for dyadic functions with axis.

   The APL character itself was designed in a way that made it easy to
remember which functions it represented.

   Unfortunately this 1:1 relationship between APL characters and
interpreter functions did not scale very well.  As the number of
functions increased, a new and, at that time, better scalable concept
was introduced: тОХ-functions (and variables).  The APL standards define
only a small number (less than 20) of them, but different APL vendors
were eagerly adding more system functions to represent their proprietary
extensions to th APL language.  And so did GNU APL. With тОХ-functions the
original visual appearance that helped to remember the many functions
was replaced by abbreviations.  That is, for example, тОХAV stands for the
Atomic Vector, тОХTS for Time Stamp, and so forth.

   As of this writing, the GNU APL interpreter has more than 100
non-standard functions for various purposes.  For such a large number
the тОХ-function approach is no longer scalable (try to remember 100
abbreviations and think about the readability of the code using them!).
Rather than adding a new тОХ-function for every new function, GNU APL
tries to keep the number of тОХ-functions as small as reasonable and by
grouping several interpreter functions into sub-function of a single
top-level тОХ-function.

   We call such a top-level тОХ-function a function group.  The
sub-function functions of a function group are somehow related by their
purpose.  The function groups of GNU APL are:

   тАв тМ╣: a collection of matrix factorizations (aka.  decompositions)
   тАв тОХCR: a collection of data conversions (formerly known as monadic
     Charater Representations
   тАв тОХFFT: a collection of Fast Fourier Transformations
   тАв тОХFIO: a collection of File I/O functions
   тАв тОХMX: a collection of Matrix functions functions
   тАв тОХRVAL: generation of Random APL Values
   тАв SQL: an interface to SQL databases

   The syntax for function groups has evolved in 3 phases as elucidated
in the following.

* Menu:

* Phase 1: Numerical Axis Argument::
* Phase 2: String Axis Argument::
* Phase 3: Member Notation::
* Subfunction Lists::


File: apl.info,  Node: Phase 1: Numerical Axis Argument,  Next: Phase 2: String Axis Argument,  Up: Function Groups

2.3.1 Phase 1: Numerical Axis Argument
--------------------------------------

In the first phase, the number of functions per function group (at that
time тОХCR and тОХFIO) was fairly small.  A sub-function of the function
group was selected as follows:

   тАв If all functions in the function group were monadic (as is the case
     in тОХCR), then the sub-function was selected by the left argument of
     the function group.
   тАв Otherwise (as is the case in тОХFIO) the individual sub-function
     could be monadic, dyadic, or nomadic and the sub-function was
     selected by an axis argument of the function group.

   For example:

           4 тОХCR B          тНЭ format B in a "boxed" fashion
           18 тОХCR B         тНЭ convert APL string B to an UTF8-encoded byte vector

           тОХFIO[3] B        тНЭ fopen file B for reading
           A тОХFIO[3] B      тНЭ fopen file B with mode A

   In both cases was the sub-function selector an integer scalar.


File: apl.info,  Node: Phase 2: String Axis Argument,  Next: Phase 3: Member Notation,  Prev: Phase 1: Numerical Axis Argument,  Up: Function Groups

2.3.2 Phase 2: String Axis Argument
-----------------------------------

Shortly after introducing the syntax of phase 1, GNU APL users began to
develop an APL workspace named FILE_IO. This workspace contains one APL
wrapper function for each numerical тОХFIO sub-function selector.  These
wrappers were trivial one-liners like these:

           тИЗZh тЖР As FIOтИЖfopen Bs
           тНЭтНЭ fopen(Bs, As) filename Bs
            Zh тЖР As тОХFIO[3] Bs
           тИЗ

           тИЗZh тЖР FIOтИЖfopen_ro Bs
           тНЭтНЭ fopen(Bs, "r") filename Bs
            Zh тЖР тОХFIO[3] Bs
           тИЗ

   APL programs would )COPY this workspace and then use its normal
defined functions instead of тОХFIO with an axis argument or тОХCR with a
left argument.  The development of the FILE_IO suggested that APL users
have a preference of names over numbers to select a sub-function.

   GNU APL accommodated this preference by allowing sub-function names
(APL strings) as sub-function selectors.  These names were usually the
same as the C library function that implemented them.

   The phase 1 example above would now become the slightly better
readable:

           'style_boxed' тОХCR B        тНЭ format B in a "boxed" fashion
           'string_to_UTF8' тОХCR B     тНЭ convert APL string B to UTF8

           тОХFIO['fopen'] B            тНЭ fopen file B for reading
           A тОХFIO['fopen'] B          тНЭ fopen file B with mode A


File: apl.info,  Node: Phase 3: Member Notation,  Next: Subfunction Lists,  Prev: Phase 2: String Axis Argument,  Up: Function Groups

2.3.3 Phase 3: Member Notation
------------------------------

The third phase aims at further improving the readability.  It replaces
the axis argument with a member notation.  The phase 1 and 2 examples
above would now become:

           тОХCR.style_boxed B       тНЭ format B in a "boxed" fashion
           тОХCR.string_to_UTF8 B    тНЭ convert APL string B to UTF8

           тОХFIO.fopen B            тНЭ fopen file B for reading
           A тОХFIO.fopen B          тНЭ fopen file B with mode A


File: apl.info,  Node: Subfunction Lists,  Prev: Phase 3: Member Notation,  Up: Function Groups

2.3.4 Subfunction Lists
-----------------------

If the number of sub-functions becomes large, then remembering all
sub-function names of a function group is still a problem.  To avoid the
need to consult other documentation while programming, all function
groups provide lists that show their sub-functions and their syntax.

   Let FOO be a function group.  Then:

   тАв FOO "" shows a list of sub-functions, and
   тАв FOO тНм shows the syntaces (as per phase 1, 2, or 3) of them.


File: apl.info,  Node: Colored Output,  Next: Comparison Rules,  Prev: Function Groups,  Up: Non-standard GNU APL Features

2.4 Colored Output
==================

The APL interpreter gets its input from the standard input (stdin),
which is normally connected to the userтАЩs keyboard, but can also be a
file if APL scripting, the тАШfтАЩ option, or the тАШTтАЩ option is used.

   The APL interpreter prints its results on either the standard output
(stdout) for normal APL output, or to the error output (stderr) for
additional trouble-shooting information.

   You can print the 3 channels stdin, stdout, and stderr in different
colors by means of the debug command ]XTERM. Command ]XTERM ON enables
colored output while ]XTERM OFF disables it (for example to avoid
annoying ANSI Escape sequences when forwarding stdout or stderr to a
file).

   Default colored output assumes a terminal (-emulation) that
understands ANSI (or VT100) Escape sequences.  The xterm that comes with
most recent GNU/Linux distributions is a perfect choice supporting both
colors and UTF-8 (Unicode) encoded character I/O.

   Non-ANSI terminals, as well as other colors than the default ones,
can be configured in the тАЩpreferencesтАЩ file.  The тАЩpreferencesтАЩ file
also contains a description of all possible color settings.


