2.5 Comparison Rules
====================

Both IBM APL2 and the ISO standard require that the arguments of <, тЙд,
тЙе, and > (but not of = or тЙа) are integer or real numbers.  As a
consequence, the argument(s) of тНЛ or тНТ (which require comparison) must
also be a vector of integer or real numbers.

   In contrast, GNU APL also allows the comparison of characters and
numbers or the comparison of complex numbers according to the following,
more general, rules.

   Let A and B be two APL values to be compared.  The final result of
comparing A and B is the first verdict (i.e.  either A < B, or A > B, or
A = B) obtained when following the rules below in the indicated order:

  1. Comparison by rank: if (тН┤тН┤A) < (тН┤тН┤B) then A < B and vice versa.

  2. Comparison by shape: if (тН┤A) < (тН┤B) then A < B and vice versa.  The
     first differing shape item (from the left) decides.

  3. Comparison of ravel elements: at this point (тН┤A) тЙб (тН┤B). If all
     corresponding ravel elements of A and B are equal (i.e.  tolerantly
     equal within тОХCT as defined in the ISO standard) then A = B.

     Otherwise let A1 and B1 be the first corresponding ravel elements
     of A and B with A1 тЙа B1.  If A1 < B1 then A < B and vice versa.
     The comparison A1 < B1 is made according to the following rules 4 -
     8 below.

  4. Comparison by depth:

        тАв If A1 and B1 are both nested: the rules 1 - 3 above are
          (recursively) applied to corresponding ravel elements of тКГA1
          and тКГB1 until a verdict is obtained.

        тАв if A1 is simple and B1 is nested then A < B and vice versa.

        тАв otherwise (i.e.  A1 and B1 are both simple): A < B if A1 < B1
          according to rules 5 - 8 below and vice versa.

  5. Comparison by Unicode: if A1 and B1 are both character values and
     (тОХUCS A1) < (тОХUCS B1) then A < B and vice versa.

  6. Comparison by type: If A1 is a character and B1 is numeric, then A
     < B and vice versa.

  7. Comparison by numeric value: if A1 and B1 are both numeric values
     then:

        тАв Comparison by real part: if (9тЧЛA1) < (9тЧЛB1) then A < B and
          vice versa.

        тАв Comparison by imaginary part: otherwise if (11тЧЛA1) < (11тЧЛB1)
          then A < B and vice versa.

  8. Otherwise: A = B.

   Another way of describing the rules above is that the comparison of
two values is comprised of sub-comparisons of certain properties of the
values in the following order:

   тАв the ranks of the values,
   тАв the shapes of the values,
   тАв the first differing ravel element (in row-major order) of the
     values,
   тАв the depths of the differing ravel elements,
   тАв the types (character vs.  numeric) of the differing ravel elements,
   тАв the Unicodes of the differing ravel elements (if applicable)
   тАв the real parts of numeric values,
   тАв the imaginary parts of numeric values,

   Note: Rules 1 and 2 above are only relevant for comparisons made in
the context of sorting (i.e.  for тНЛ or тНТ).  This is because for =, тЙа, <,
тЙд, тЙе, or > either a RANK ERROR or a LENGTH ERROR is raised if the ranks
or shapes of A and B do not match:

           (9 8) < (1 2 3)
     LENGTH ERROR
           9 8<1 2 3
           ^  ^

           тНЛ(9 8) (1 2 3)
     1 2

   The reason for comparing complex numbers first by their real parts
and then by their imaginary part and not, for example, first by their
magnitude and then by their angle is that the chosen order gives more
consistent results when comparing near-complex numbers or their true
real companions.  For example, a magnitude first comparison of complex
numbers would make ┬п2 < ┬п1 < ┬п2J1E┬п20 for the near-complex number
┬п2J1E┬п20.

   CAUTION: The comparison of two strings (i.e.  nested character
vectors) may give unexpected results because shorter strings come before
longer strings.  For example, тАЩZooтАЩ comes before тАЩAdamтАЩ even though one
might expect the opposite.

           Z[тНЛZ тЖР 'Adam' 'Zoo']
      Zoo Adam

           Z[тНЛZ тЖР 'Adam' 'Zora']
      Adam Zora

   This pitfall can be avoided by enforcing the same length for all
strings being compared or sorted.  A simple way to achieve that is the
use of тКВ[2]тКГ like this (assuming тОХIOтЖР1):

           Z[тНЛZ тЖР тКВ[2]тКГ 'Adam' 'Zoo']
      Adam Zoo

           Z[тНЛZ тЖР тКВ[2]тКГ 'Adam' 'Zora']
      Adam Zora


File: apl.info,  Node: Complex Numbers,  Next: Debug Commands,  Prev: Comparison Rules,  Up: Non-standard GNU APL Features

2.6 Complex Numbers
===================

Complex numbers are fully supported.


File: apl.info,  Node: Debug Commands,  Next: Direct Functions (Lambdas),  Prev: Complex Numbers,  Up: Non-standard GNU APL Features

2.7 Debug Commands
==================

In addition to the classical APL commands like )LOAD or )SAVE, GNU APL
has a number of debug commands for debugging purposes.  Regular APL
commands start with ) and print their output on stdout.  Debug commands
start with ] and print their output on stderr.  Normally you cannot
easily distinguish between stdout and stderr, but another GNU APL
feature, colored output, uses different colors for stdout and stderr.

   Type )HELP or ]HELP in the interpreter for a list of all commands
available.


File: apl.info,  Node: Direct Functions (Lambdas),  Next: Commands )COPY_ONCE )DUMP and DUMP-HTML,  Prev: Debug Commands,  Up: Non-standard GNU APL Features

2.8 Direct Functions (Lambdas)
==============================

GNU APL supports direct functions (aka.  lambdas), but only in a rather
limited form.

   Direct functions must be defined entirely on a single line.

   Corollary: Multi-line strings and multi-line literals may not be used
in the definition of a GNU APL lambda.

* Menu:

* Named Lambdas::
* Unnamed Lambdas::
* Limitations of GNU APL Lambdas::


File: apl.info,  Node: Named Lambdas,  Next: Unnamed Lambdas,  Up: Direct Functions (Lambdas)

2.8.1 Named Lambdas
-------------------

A statement of the form

           FUN тЖР { body_statement }

   creates a named lambda.  The body_statement(s) may contain the
special variable names тН║ and тН╡ as well as the special function names тН╢
and тН╣ which are replaced by the actual arguments of the lambda when the
lambda is executed.  The valence of the lambda is determined as follows:

   тАв If тН╢ and тН╣ are present then the lambda is a dyadic operator.
   тАв If only тН╢ is present then the lambda is a monadic operator.
   тАв If neither тН╢ nor тН╣ is present then the lambda is a normal defined
     function.
   тАв If both тН║ and тН╡ are present in the body_statement(s) then the
     operator or defined function is dyadic.
   тАв If only тН╡ is present then the operator or defined is monadic.
   тАв If neither тН║ nor тН╡ is present then the lambda is niladic.
   тАв Lambdas with the left value argument тН║ but without the right value
     argument тН╡ are invalid (SYNTAX ERROR).

   There is a noteworthy pitfall related to niladic named lambdas.
Recalling to the fundamental APL evaluation rule:

   All functions execute according to their position in an expression.
The rightmost function whose arguments are available is evaluated first

   implies that a niladic function is evaluated first (because it has no
arguments and consequently no arguments that are not available).
Therefore in an expression such as:

     NAME тЖР { statement(s) }

   will the niladic lambda { statement(s) } be evaluated before the
assignment, The name NAME is therefore the result of the niladic lambda
and not the definition of a niladic lambda with that name.  IOW: the
example above does not create a niladic named lambda, but rather a
normal variable NAME whose value is the result of evaluating statement.

   Corollary: Creating niladic named lambdas is impossible.

   GNU APL supports an axis argument in normal defined functions and
operators.  In lambda expressions the Greek letter ╧З (Chi) is the
variable name for an axis argument.

   The way a named lambda is implemented in GNU APL is that the
assignment of the form:

           FUN тЖР { body_expression }

   is translated to a two-line function тОХFX тАЩlambda_headerтАЩ
тАЩbody_expressionтАЩ.

   For example:

           )FNS

           SUM тЖР { тН║ + тН╡ }

   is translated to a two-line function тОХFX тАЩlambda_headerтАЩ
тАЩbody_expressionтАЩ.

   For example:

           )FNS

           SUM тЖР { тН║ + тН╡ }
           )FNS
     SUM

           тИЗSUM[тОХ]тИЗ
     DEFN ERROR+
           тИЗSUM[тОХ]тИЗ
                  ^
           )MORE
     function is a lambda

   Named lambdas are included in function lists like )FNS along with
other defined functions.  They can not be edited with the тИЗ-edidor, but
can be displayed using тОХCR тАЩnameтАЩ:

           тОХCR 'SUM'
     ╬╗тЖРтН║ ╬╗1 тН╡
     ╬╗тЖР тН║ + тН╡

   The lambda_header is automatically deduced from the presence or
absence of the variable names (тН║, тН╡, and ╧З) and function names (тН╢ and тН╣)
in the body_expression and from whether the body_expression is empty (no
╬╗тЖР) or not (i.e.  with ╬╗тЖР).

   It is possible to specify local variables that work exactly like
their companions in normal defined functions.  Please note that this is
different from some other APL interpreters which treat all variables in
lambda bodies as local variables.  The syntax for specifying local
variables is the same as for the header in normal defined functions:
they are added at the end with semicolons as separators.  In the above
example one could add local variables C and D like this:

           SUM тЖР { тН║ + тН╡ ;C;D }

           тОХCR 'SUM'
     ╬╗тЖРтН║ ╬╗1 тН╡;C;D
     ╬╗тЖР тН║ + тН╡

   If a named lambda is created inside a defined function, then the name
of the lambda (i.e.  the name left of тЖР { ...  }) can be made a local
variable of the function in which the named lambda is created.  This
creates a lambda with local scope.

   Please note that the above only describes the current implementation
of named lambda in GNU APL. A consequence of that implementation is that
the symbols тН║, тН╡, ╧З, тН╢, тН╣, and ╬╗ are pretty much behaving like user
defined variables.  In particular, they can be used outside named or
unnamed lambdas.  However, that may change in the future and therefore
such use of тН║, тН╡, ╧З, тН╢, тН╣, and ╬╗ outside is certainly a bad idea.

   As of this writing, GNU APL lambdas support multiple statements,
separated by тЧК.  This feature is experimental, not portable, and should
be avoided where possible.  In GNU APL, the value of a multi-statement
lambda is the value of the last statement and this differs from the
semantics of multi-statements in other APL interpreters!


