2.11.3.4 ]KEYB USER
...................

]KEYB USER does not try to figure the current keyboard mapping but
rather displays a static file provided by the user.  This mode is a
fallback for the case where the other modes are not able to produce a
correct keyboard layout.  The user can take the output of ]KEYB GUESS as
a starting point and correct the deviations from the actual keyboard
layout.

   The name of file shown with ]KEYB USER can be configured in one of
the preferences files.


File: apl.info,  Node: ]KEYB GUESS,  Next: Optional ]KEYB arguments,  Prev: ]KEYB USER,  Up: The ]KEYB command

2.11.3.5 ]KEYB GUESS
....................

]KEYB GUESS does not try to figure the current keyboard mapping but
rather displays the layout that the various keyboard configuration files
that are shipped with GNU APL are likely to produce.  The layout is a
standard US APL keyboard.


File: apl.info,  Node: Optional ]KEYB arguments,  Prev: ]KEYB GUESS,  Up: The ]KEYB command

2.11.3.6 Optional ]KEYB arguments
.................................

]KEYB XMOD KEYS runs xmodmap -pke, but first shows the assumed physical
layout of the keyboard.  By comparing the first half of the output with
the second half, one can see how xmodmap mapes keycodes to Unicode
characters.  For example:

