   As the Source: GNU APL builtin in the example above indicates, this
is the layout assumed by GNU APL, which may differ from the true layout
of your keybord.  For example, say key R with ALT pressed does not
produce тН┤.  The Unicode for тН┤ is :

           тОХUCS "тН┤"                    тНЭ Unicode for тН┤
     9076
           ,5 тОХCR 256 256 тКд тОХUCS "тН┤"   тНЭ Unicode for тН┤ in hex
     2374

   One can check if the keycodes displayed by ]KEYB XMOD KEYS are
correct with a programm called xev (which is normally pre-installed in
most GNU/Linux distributions.  After starting xev and hitting the R key
several times (because it also shows many other unrelated events), one
can see the corresponding key events:

           ...
     KeyPress event, serial 38, synthetic NO, window 0x3c00001,
         root 0x75c, subw 0x0, time 35629183, (-590,275), root:(284,737),
         state 0x0, keycode 27 (keysym 0x72, r), same_screen YES,
         XLookupString gives 1 bytes: (72) "r"
         XmbLookupString gives 1 bytes: (72) "r"
         XFilterEvent returns: False

   So we see that the R key does indeed have the keycode 27.  Next we
look at the line for key keycode 27 in the xmodmap.apl file:

     keycode  27 =  r               R               U2374

   This line tells us that, when the R is hit, the following Unicodes
shall be emitted:

   тАв the Unicode for (lowercase) r if neither SHIFT nor ALT is held
     down,
   тАв the Unicode for (uppercase) R if SHIFT is pressed and ALT is not,
   тАв the Unicode for тН┤ = $2374 if ALT is pressed and SHIFT is not.

   The line could have had a fourth entry (for SHIFT and ALT pressed);
if that entry is, like above, missing then the same Unicode is emitted
for both ALT and SHIFT+ALT. Likewise, if the second entry is missing
then the same code is used for SHIFT and no SHIFT. This is, for example,
the case for keycode 36 with keysym Return (the key that is sometimes
labelled Enter and sometimes Return and whose keysym is independent of
the state of the SHIFT and ALT keys.  In the xmodmap the keysyms can be
specified in multiple ways: as ASCII characters (like r and R above, as
Unicodes like U2374 above, or as symbols like NoSymbol or Return, which
are defined in files /usr/include/X11/X.h and
/usr/include/X11/keysymdef.h:

     #define NoSymbol         0L  /* special KeySym */
     #define XK_Return    0xff0d  /* Return, enter */

   Given the explanations above, the troubleshooting of keyboard
mappings becomes simple (though somewhat tedious in the details):

  1. do ]KEYB XMOD KEYS in GNU APL to display the keycodes, then
  2. run xev in a different window and verify, for every key on the
     keyboard, that the keycode shown by xev is the one shown by ]KEYB
     XMOD KEYS, then
  3. do ]KEYB XMOD in GNU APL to display the keysyms, then
  4. edit the xmodmap.apl file (or whatever other file ws used as the
     argument for the xmondmap command) to see if the Unicodes for every
     keycode line are correct.  In that test:
        тАв the first keysym is used for the lowercase character, i.e.  if
          neither SHIFT nor ALT are pressed,
        тАв the second keysym is used for the uppercase character, i.e.
          if SHIFT is pressed and ALT is not.  If no second keysym is
          present, then the first keysym is used instead,
        тАв the third keysym is used for the character that shall be
          emitted when the ALT key is pressed and the SHIFT is not.  If
          no third keysym is present then nothing is emitted, and
        тАв the fourth keysym is used for the character that shall be
          emitted when both the ALT key and the SHIFT are pressed.  If
          no fourth keysym is present then the behavior is the same as
          for ALT without SHIFT.


