2.20.2 Monadic тКдтИи and тКдтН▒
------------------------

тКд=, тКдтЙа, and тКдтН▓ do not have a monadic form, but тКдтИз, тКдтИи, and тКдтН▒ do.
Formally monadic тКдтИи and тКдтН▒ are dyadic тКдтИи and тКдтН▒ with a left argument of
0:

           тКдтИи B    тЖРтЖТ    0 тКдтИи B      тНЭ real B to nearby integer
           тКдтН▒ B    тЖРтЖТ    0 тКдтН▒ B      тНЭ bit-wise Not

   Even though Or-ing a Boolean vector with 0 itself has no effect, the
monadic тКдтИи and тКдтН▒ are still useful due to their side effects: conversion
from near-integer float values to integers (monadic тКдтИи and inversion of
the bits (monadic тКдтН▒, The latter is needed since тИ╝ has a monadic form
and, as a consequence, тКдтИ╝ was not an option for a bit-wise Not function.

   Monadic тКдтН▒ B is the bit-wise Not function of its argument:

   тКдтН▒ B тЖРтЖТ 2тКе ~(64тН┤2)тКдB

   Monadic тКдтИи B converts near-integer values B into true integers:

           26 тОХCR    1            тНЭ integer
     16
           26 тОХCR    1.1          тНЭ real
     32
           26 тОХCR    1├╖1          тНЭ integer
     16
           26 тОХCR    1.1├╖1.1      тНЭ real
     32
           26 тОХCR    тКдтИи 1.1├╖1.1   тНЭ integer
     16

   That also works for complex numbers with a near-zero imaginary part:

           26 тОХCR    1.1J0├╖1.1      тНЭ real
     32
           26 тОХCR    тКдтИи 1.1J0├╖1.1      тНЭ integer
     16

   As a matter of fact, тКдтИи works for all near-Gaussian complex numbers,
but the effect is not visible with 26 тОХCR since Gaussian and
non-Gaussian complex numbers have the same cell type in GNU APL.


