2.21 тКд (Encode) with Axis
=========================

The dyadic primitive function A тКе B (Decode) computes the values of B in
a number system with radices A. The most common case is a homogeneous
radix, i.e.  all items of A are the same.  In that case the radix A can
be specified as a scalar A which will be scalar-extended to the length
of B (more precisely: to тЖСтН┤B). For example:

           2 2 2 2 тКе 1 1 0 1
     13

           2тКе1 1 0 1              тНЭ scalar extension of 2 to length 4
     13

           ((тН┤B)тН┤2) тКд BтЖР1 1 0 1   тНЭ scalar extension of 2 to тЖСтН┤B
     13

   The dyadic primitive function A тКд B (Encode) computes the
representation of B in a number system whose radices are A. The most
common case is again a homogeneous radix A. In this sense, Encode is the
inverse function of Decode.  Unfortunately Encode can not scalar extend
the radix A. This is because the shapes of its arguments do not provide
sufficient information to determine the radix length that shall be used.
As a consequence:

   тАв the user needs to provide the radix A as a vector with identical
     items and with a length that is suitable for the items in B,
   тАв if more radix items than needed are provided, then the result
     contains leading 0s (which is sort of OK because no information is
     lost), but
   тАв if less radix items than needed are provided, then an oberflow
     occurs and the result is truncated.  This is awkward because, for
     example

                2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 тКд 1000     тНЭ radix too short for 1000
          1 1 1 0 1 0 0 0

                2 тКе 1 1 1 0 1 0 0 0        тНЭ therefore not 1000 !!!
          232
                232 + (2тЛЖ8) + (2тЛЖ9)        тНЭ add missing items
          1000

   тАв The IBM APL2 language reference manual proposes to use the APL
     expression тМК1тИг+AтНЯ(тИгB)+A=0 for the optimal length of the radix A.

   We call a radix length тН┤A optimal if it is neither too long nor to
short.  In that case the result has no leading zeros and B тЙб AтКеAтКдN. For
an optimal radix length are AтКд and AтКе the inverse functions of each
other.

   In order to improve on this, GNU APL offers the possibility to
automatically (and without using AтНЯB) compute the optimal radix length
from A and B. The solution implemented in GNU APL is to provide the
optimal radix length as an axis argument.  There are two different cases
for the axis argument:

   тАв If the optimal radix length is known, say N > 0, then the radix
     length is given as axis argument N>0.  In this case the left
     argument of AтКдB is slightly simplified:

                (NтН┤тЖСA) тКд B   тЖРтЖТ   A тКд[N] B   тНЭ optimal radix length N>0 is known

     This case frequently occurs when integer(s) B are encoded into
     hexadecimal 8-bit (i.e.  radix length = 2 hex digits), 16-bit words
     (i.e.  radix length = 4 hex digits), 32-bit longs (i.e.  radix
     length = 8 hex digits), or 64-bit long longs (i.e.  radix length =
     16 hex digits).

   тАв Otherwise the radix length is not known; this case is specified as
     axis argument 0.  This is also the case where тМК1тИг+AтНЯ(тИгB)+A=0 would
     be needed, and it simplifies AтКдB considerably:

                ((тМК1тИг+AтНЯ(тИгB)+A=0)тН┤тЖСA) тКд B   тЖРтЖТ   A тКд [0]B   тНЭ unknown radix length

   Please note the following:

   тАв Obviously the case N>0 is faster than the case N=0 because the user
     has taken over radix length computation.  However, AтКд[N]B is still
     faster than the classical (NтН┤тЖСA)тКдB.

   тАв If all items in B are non-negative, then the case N=0 uses the
     optimal radix length for unsigned numbers, i.e.  without a sign.
     The result can be used in what is known as unsigned base-A
     arithmetic.

   тАв If some item of B is negative, then the case N=0 uses a radix
     length that includes a sign (aka.  twoтАЩs complement arithmetic if
     A=2).  The sign is 0 for the non-negative items of B and A-1 for
     the negative items of B (= 1 for binary encodings).

   Examples:
           2тКд[4] 13           тНЭ 4 digit radix, positive B
     1 1 0 1

           2тКе1 1 0 1          тНЭ proof
     13

           2тКд[5] ┬п13          тНЭ 5 digit radix, negative B
     1 0 0 1 1

           32 - 2тКе1 0 0 1 1   тНЭ proof
     13



