2.23.2.2 тМ╣[X] B: Various Factorizations of B
............................................

The numeric scalar X chooses one of several algorithms that computes a
factorization (aka.  decomposition) of a matrix B:

   тАв тМ╣[1]B computes a QR-factorization of B. It uses the algorithm
     published by Garry Helzer in APL Quote Quad in 1990.  This
     algorithm is always available.

   тАв тМ╣[2]B also computes a QR-factorization of B. However, it uses a
     libgsl based algorithm and is therefore only available if libgsl
     was installed when GNU APL was ./configureтАЩd..

   тАв тМ╣[3]B computes a RQ-factoriztion of B. It also requires libgsl.

   тАв тМ╣[4]B computes a LQ-factoriztion of B. It also requires libgsl.

   тАв тМ╣[5]B computes a QL-factoriztion of B. It also requires libgsl.

   тАв тМ╣[6]B computes a LU-factoriztion of B. It also requires libgsl.

   тАв тМ╣[TOL]B with a small real TOL. This variant is obsolete and only
     provided for backward compatibility with older versions of GNU APL
     (and is subject to being removed at some point in time).  It uses
     the Helzer algorithm with TOL instead of тОХCT. New code should not
     use тМ╣[TOL] but rather тМ╣[1] or тМ╣[2] after setting тОХCTтЖРTOL.

   The Helzer algorithm recursively factors a N├ЧN matrix, a (N-1)├Ч(N-1)
matrix, a (N-2)├Ч(N-2) matrix, and so forth.  After every step of that
recursion, all matrix items that are close to 0.0 are set to exactly
0.0.  The meaning of close is defined by тОХCT in тМ╣[1]B (resp.  TOL in the
obsolete case above).

   In the Helzer algorithm, GNU APL uses тОХCT as the tolerance TOL which
decides if a matrix item close to 0.0 shall be set to 0.0 or not (APL
functions A TOL X and A CPR B in the Helzer paper).  The Helzer paper
leaves it open how to implement A TOL X and A CPR B). GNU APL uses the
example implementation given in the Helzer paper.  The TOL and CPR
functions seem to be related to what is elsewhere known as the condition
number of the matrix that is being factorized.  In the libgsl based
algotithms is тОХCT not used.

   The factorizations тМ╣[1], тМ╣[2], тМ╣[3], тМ╣[4], and тМ╣[5] return a (nested)
vector (Q T Ti) where Q is orthogonal, T is (upper or lower) triangular,
and Ti is T^{-1}.

   Let тН┤B = (M N) and let min_MN = min(M, N). Then the factorization
тМ╣[6] returns a nested vector (P U L) where:
   тАв vector P is a permutation of тН│M,
   тАв matrix L is lower triangular with shape (M min_MN) and all of its
     diagonal items equal to 1.0.,
   тАв matrix U is upper triangular with shape (min_MN N), and, most
     importantly,
   тАв B[P;] = LтИШU.


