2.23.2.6 A тМ╣[9] B: Divide Polynomial A by Polynomial B (univariate)
...................................................................

The scalar APL primitives + and - can be used for vectors and for
polynomials alike.  In contrast, the division of a polynomial A by a
polynomial B is different from the scalar division A├╖B and is also
different from the matrix division A тМ╣.├Ч B.

   Dyadic A тМ╣[9] B aka.  A тМ╣.poly_divide B fills this gap and computes
the quotient of two polynomials.  Since polynomials form a ring (and not
a field) the quotient is not always a polynomial (at least not one with
non-negative exponents).  For this reason A тМ╣.poly_divide B performs a
division with remainder and the result is a pair (Quotient, Remainder)
where Remainder is a polynomial with a degree smaller that the degree of
polynomial B. That is, тН┤Remainder = ┬п1+тН┤B.

   NOTE: A тМ╣[9] B is limited to polynomials with 1 indeterminant.


File: apl.info,  Node: A тМ╣[10] B: Divide Polynomial A by Polynomial B (multivariate),  Next: A тМ╣[11] B: Divide Polynomial A by Polynomial B (with order),  Prev: A тМ╣[9] B: Divide Polynomial A by Polynomial B (univariate),  Up: The Impact of тОХCT for тМ╣

2.23.2.7 A тМ╣[10] B: Divide Polynomial A by Polynomial B (multivariate)
......................................................................

The limitiation of A тМ╣[10] B to handle only polynomials with one
indeterminan is lifted with A тМ╣[10] aka.  A тМ╣.poly_divideN B. The suffix
N shall indicate that the number off indefinites is > 1.  However, some
caution needs to be exercized when using this function, as described in
the following.

   A polynomial is the sum of zero or more terms.  The terms of a
polynomial are commonly called monomials.

   Tip: to list, for example, all possible monomials of a polymomial
with three indeterminants x, y, and z and at most powers of 3:

           тНЭ show all monomials of indeterminants x, y, z
            тНЭ and max.powers 0, 1, and 2 (in lexicographic order)
           тНЭ
           тМ╣.poly_print 3 3 3тН┤1
     x┬▓y┬▓z┬▓ + x┬▓y┬▓z + x┬▓y┬▓ + x┬▓yz┬▓ + x┬▓yz + x┬▓y + x┬▓z┬▓ + x┬▓z + x┬▓ + xy┬▓z┬▓ + xy┬▓z +
           xy┬▓ + xyz┬▓ + xyz + xy + xz┬▓ + xz + x + y┬▓z┬▓ + y┬▓z + y┬▓ + yz┬▓ + yz + y +
           z┬▓ + z + 1

   In the set of all monomials an order, that is a relation < between
any two elements of the set needs to be defined.  In the simple cases of
dividing integers or polynomials with only one indeterminant the order <
is canonical:

   тАв order of integer: 0 < 1 < 2 < 3 ...
   тАв order of polynomials: xтБ░ < x┬╣ < x┬▓ < x┬│ ...

   An order between monomials need not only satisfy the general
requirements of an order (i.e.  being reflexive, antisymmetric, and
transitive), but also the following:

   тАв if x^{тН║} < x^{╬▓} then x^{╬│}x^{тН║} < x^{╬│}x^{╬▓} for all ╬│, and
   тАв M тЙе 0 for every monomial M

   The general problem with multivariate polynomials (i.e.  polynomials
with more than one indeterminant, such as x┬▓ + y┬▓) is then that the
quotient and remainder of two multivariate polinomials is not unique but
depend on the order defined between its monomials.  The division of
integers and of polynomials with one indeterminant is based on their
canonical order, which results in a unique quotient and a unique
remainder in these cases.  In contrast there can be several different
orders between the monomials of a multivariate polynomial, and these
different orders leads to different quotients and remainders.

   For example:
     Let
           f = x2y + xy2 + y2,
           gтВБ = xy тИТ 1, and
           gтВВ = y┬▓ тИТ 1.

     Dividing f by gтВБ and then by gтВВ gives:

           f = (x + y)(xy тИТ 1)  +  (y┬▓ тИТ 1)  +  (x + y + 1)
             = (x + y) gтВБ       +      gтВВ    +  (x + y + 1)

     However, dividing f by gтВВ and then by gтВБ gives:

           f = x(xy тИТ 1)  +  (x + 1)(y┬▓ тИТ 1)  +  (2x + 1)
             = x gтВБ       +  ((x + 1) gтВВ      +  (2x + 1)


   This ambiguity is resolved by always dividing a polynomial by its
largest term, where the largest term is in turn defined by the order of
the mononomials that was chosen.  IOW: a monomial order defines the
which of the monomials of a polynomial is its largest monomials, and in
every iteration of the division the largest monomial is being
annihilated (by subtracting a multiple of the divisor from it).

   Now, a commonly used order in the division of polynomials, and also
the order used by A тМ╣[10] B, is the lexicographic order of the
polynomials.  *Note тМ╣[11] B Scan Polynomial B::.

   For example: x < x┬▓, xy < xyz, y < xтБ╕, and yтБ╕ < x in the
lexicographic order.

   With these prerequisites, the division algorithm of GNU APL (which
was inspired by
<https://lall.stanford.edu/ee464/lectures/groebner_bases.pdf>) is this:

           Let LT(p) denote the largest term in polynomial p, and let       (1)

           qтВБ = qтВВ = ... = qтВЩ = 0   тНЭ quotient                              (1a)
           r  = 0                   тНЭ remainder                             (1b)
           p = f                    тНЭ dividend                              (1c)

           while p тЙа 0:                                                     (2)
                 let i be the smallest i such that LT(gс╡в) divides LT(p).    (3)
                 if such an i exists then:                                  (3a)
                       qс╡в = qс╡в + LT(p) ├╖ LT(gс╡в)                             (4a)
                       p = p - gс╡в ├Ч LT(r) ├╖ LT(gс╡в)                          (4b)
                 otherwise:                                                 (3b)
                       r = r + LT(p)                                        (5a)
                       p = p - LT(gс╡в)                                       (5b)

   The algorithm divides polynomial f by polynomial g = gтВБ + gтВВ + ...  +
gтВЩ and yields a quotient q = qтВБ + qтВВ + ...  + qтВШ and a remainder r = rтВБ
+ rтВВ + ...  + rтВЦ.  In every iteration the largest term in p is
annihilated by "moving" it to either iq (after dividing it by LT(gс╡в) if
that is possible) or else to r (if not).  Obviously:

   тАв The divisor g does not change at all,
   тАв p gets shorter and shorter in each iteration and therefore the
     algorithm terminates after at most n iterations.  In addition the
     subtraction in 4b certainly annihilates the leading term of p, but
     could also annihilate other monomials of p (which then also reduces
     the number of iterations performed).
   тАв The quotient q grows as new quotients are being added in step 4b.
   тАв The remainder r also grows as new items are added in step 5a.  In
     the integer and polynomial with one indeterminant cases is the
     length of the remainder limited by the degree of the dividend (so
     the remainder of dividing e.g.  x┬│ + ax┬▓ + bx + c by anything has
     always no more than 3 momomials).  In contrast a polynomial with a
     max.  power of, say, 3 but 4 indeterminants can have up to 4тБ┤ = 256
     momomials.


File: apl.info,  Node: A тМ╣[11] B: Divide Polynomial A by Polynomial B (with order),  Next: тМ╣[11] B Scan Polynomial B,  Prev: A тМ╣[10] B: Divide Polynomial A by Polynomial B (multivariate),  Up: The Impact of тОХCT for тМ╣

2.23.2.8 A тМ╣[11] B: Divide Polynomial A by Polynomial B (with order)
....................................................................

As explained above, different monomial orders of a polynomial can lead
to different quotients and remainders when dividing them.  This iproblem
is addressed by A тМ╣[11] B aka.  A тМ╣.poly_divideNO B. The suffix NO shall
indicate that the number off indefinites is > 1, and that a user defined
monomial order shall be used.

   Let P be a polynimial.  An monomial order O for P is then a matrix
with the following properties:

   тАв O has the same shape as P: (тН┤P) тЙб (тН┤O).
   тАв тЖСO (the order value of the contant term of the polynomial) is 0

   In addition, as already mentioned above, the order defined by O shall
be consistent: if x^{тН║} < x^{╬▓} then x^{╬│}x^{тН║} < x^{╬│}x^{╬▓} for all ╬│
in O. A тМ╣.poly_divideNO B checks that тЖСO = 0 but not the consistency of
O. If the consistency condition is violated, then in the best case the
results are incorrect, and in the worst case the division algorithm may
not terminate.

   For example, given a Polynomial P, the lexicographic order of P can
be constrocted as follows:

           тНЭ construct the lexicographical order of all possible monom in P
           тНЭ
           ORDERтЖР-тОХIO-(тН┤P)тН┤тН│├Ч/тН┤P

   After an order O has been created for a polynomial P, both can be
appended to create an argument for A тМ╣.poly_divideNO B:

           тНЭ append the desired monomial order O to a polynomial P.
           тНЭ
           PO тЖР (2,тН┤P)тН┤(,P),,O

   Putting the pieces together:

           тНЭ create the dividend
           тНЭ
           "A:" AтЖРтМ╣.poly_scan "x┬│ - x┬▓ - xy┬▓ - 2x + y┬▓ + 4"
      A:    4 0  1
          ┬п2 0 ┬п1
          ┬п1 0  0
           1 0  0

           тНЭ create the divisor
           тНЭ
           "B:" BтЖРтМ╣.poly_scan "x - y"
      B:   0 ┬п1
           1  0

           тНЭ create the monomial orders for A and B
           тНЭ
           ORDER_AтЖР-тОХIO-(тН┤A)тН┤тН│├Ч/тН┤A
           ORDER_BтЖР-тОХIO-(тН┤B)тН┤тН│├Ч/тН┤B

           тНЭ append the orders to their polynomial
           тНЭ
           ARG_A тЖР (2,тН┤A)тН┤(,A),,ORDER_A
           ARG_B тЖР (2,тН┤B)тН┤(,B),,ORDER_B

           тНЭ call тМ╣.poly_divideN and poly_divideNO
           тНЭ
           (Q1 R1) тЖР     A тМ╣.poly_divideN B
           (Q2 R2) тЖР ARG_A тМ╣.poly_divideNO ARG_B

           тНЭ the result should be the same, because
           тНЭ ORDER_A is what тМ╣.poly_divideN uses.
           тНЭ
           (Q1 R1) тЙб (Q2 R2)
     1


File: apl.info,  Node: тМ╣[11] B Scan Polynomial B,  Next: A тМ╣[20] B: Integral B,  Prev: A тМ╣[11] B: Divide Polynomial A by Polynomial B (with order),  Up: The Impact of тОХCT for тМ╣

2.23.2.9 тМ╣[11] B: Scan Polynomial B
...................................

тМ╣[11] B aka.  тМ╣.poly_scan B is the inverse function of тМ╣[7] B. It
converts a string B (in the format produced by тМ╣poly_print B and returns
the corresponding APL value.

           тКвZтЖРтМ╣.poly_scan "1 + 2xy + 3y┬▓"
     1 0 3
     0 2 0

           тМ╣.poly_print Z
     2xy + 3y┬▓ + 1

   NOTE that the terms of a polynomial are commutative.  The same set of
terms, summed up in different orders, defines the same polynomial.
Therefore:

   M тЙб тМ╣.poly_scan тМ╣.poly_print M

   however:

   P тЙб тМ╣.poly_print тМ╣.poly_scan P

   holds only if the terms in P occur in the same order as produced by
тМ╣.poly_print.  The order in which тМ╣.poly_print B prints the terms of a
polynimial B is what is known as the lexicographic order, which can, in
this context, be defined as follows:

   A sequence of vectors is in lexicographic order (or: ordered
lexicographically), if every smaller item ia in the sequence comes
before every larger item b in the sequence.  Where smaller resp, larger
is defined as follows:

   тАв Let a = aтВА aтВБ ...  aтВЩ,
   тАв let b = bтВА bтВБ ...  bтВЩ,
   тАв let тИЖ = тИЖтВА тИЖтВБ ...  тИЖтВЩ with тИЖт▒╝ = bт▒╝ - aт▒╝, and
   тАв let j be the smallest j such that тИЖт▒╝ тЙа 0.  That is: the first j-1
     items of a and b are equal) and j is the first position at which
     vectors a and b differ.
   тАв Then:
        тАв If тИЖт▒╝ > 0 then a <_{lex} b (i.e.  a is smaller than b and b is
          larger than a).
        тАв Otherwise тИЖт▒╝ < 0 and then b <_{lex} a (i.e.  a is larger than
          b and b is smaller than a).

   The lexicographic order is also defined for vectors of different
lengths, but in this context all vectors compared have the same length
(number of indeterminants).


File: apl.info,  Node: A тМ╣[20] B: Integral B,  Prev: тМ╣[11] B Scan Polynomial B,  Up: The Impact of тОХCT for тМ╣

2.23.2.10 A тМ╣[20] B: Integral B
...............................

Function A тМ╣[20] B aka.  A тМ╣.integral B computes the integral of
expression B. For example:

           тНЭ monadic (same as A=1)
           тНЭ
           тМ╣.integral "sqrt(x┬│)"
     2*x*sqrt(x┬│)/5

           тНЭ A=1 : vector result
           тНЭ
           1 тМ╣.integral "sqrt(x┬│)"
     2*x*sqrt(x┬│)/5

           тНЭ A=2 : matrix result
           тНЭ
           2 тМ╣.integral "sqrt(x┬│)"
           _____
     2тЛЕxтЛЕтХ▓тХ▒  x┬│
     тФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФА
          5

   NOTE: The implementation of тМ╣.integral depends on python.  It also
depends on the python package sympy which does the actual computation of
the integral.  Normally the GNU APL ./configure script determines which
optional libraries for GNU APL are present and compiles GNU APL
accordingly.  In the python case this is not possible because python and
its packages can be installed globally (by a privilreged user such as
root) or by a unprivilreged user (e.g.  below her home directory).  It
could therefore happen that e.g.  python is available for the user that
installs GNU APL, but not for a user that uses the installed GNU APL.
The GNU APL ./configure has no way to detect such a situation.  For this
reason GNU APL checks at runtime (i.e.  when тМ╣.integral is used) if
python and sympy are installed (and raises a DOMAIN ERROR if not).

   Now to the arguments of тМ╣.integral.  The right argument B is a string
with the expression for which the integral shall be computed.  The
syntax of B ia pretty much defined by sympy.  A maybe noteworthy
difference between strings understood by тМ╣.integral and strings
understood by sympy is that powers in sympy cwhave to be written as e.g.
a**n, while тМ╣.integral also understands aтБ┐.

   The left argument A is a vector of options.  Currently only one
option is defined which defines the format of the result:

   тАв A[1]=1 : the result is a string (see example above)
   тАв A[1]=2 : the result is a character matrix (see example above).  The
     matrix is primarily created by the sympy function pretty() (which
     is unfortunately not formally specified).  For this reason is
     A[1]=2 somewhat experimental and may produce a garbled output in
     some cases.
   тАв A[1]=3 : the result is a string in a simple to parse format.
   тАв A[1]=4 : the result is a string in LATEX format.
   тАв A[1]=5 : the result is a character matrix in Math_ML format.
   тАв A[1]=6 : the result is a character matrix in Dot format.

   MathML is an XML-based industry standard for mathematical
expressions.

   Dot is a program for printing directed graphs.


