2.28 тОХDLX - KnuthтАЩs Dancing Links Algorithm
===========================================

тОХDLX is an implementation of Donald KnuthтАЩs Dancing Links Algorithm
(called DLX by Knuth himself, but is sometimes also referred to as
KnuthтАЩs Algorithm X). тОХDLX is a generic backtracking machine that can be
used to dramatically simplify problems like the 8 queens problem on a
chess board or sudokus.

   The monadic form of тОХDLX, i.e.  тОХDLX B, is a shortcut for 0 тОХDLX B.
It computes the first solution for the constraint matrix B.

   The dyadic form of тОХDLX, i.e.  A тОХDLX B, has an integer scalar A as
left argument which determines the details of the computation as
follows:

   A > 0: The algorithm tries to find all solutions, but stops when A
solutions have been found.  This is handy while debugging code using
тОХDLX. The result is a nested vector with one vector item per solution.

   A = 0: The algorithm stops when the first solution was found.  In
this case the solution is a simple (non-nested) numeric vector.

   A = ┬п1: like A > 0 but finding all solutions

   A = ┬п2: like A = 0 but instead of returning the first solution, the
number of solutions (i.e.  0 or 1), the number of backtracks, and the
number of link dances is returned as a 3-element numeric vector.

   A = ┬п3: like A = ┬п1 but instead of returning all solutions, the
number of solutions, the number of backtracks, and the number of link
dances is returned as a 3-element numeric vector.

   A = ┬п4: A number of single steps in KnuthтАЩs Algorithm are performed.
Let e.g.  AтЖР┬п4 r1 r2 r3.  Then ZтЖРA тОХDLX B is the matrix B after 3 steps
r1, r2, and r3 have been performed.  r1, r2, and r3 are valid (as per
тОХIO) row numbers of B, and a step with a given row changes B as follows:
   тАв the given row is set to 0 (this row becomes part of the final
     result),
   тАв all other rows that have a 1 or a 2 in the same column as B are set
     to 0 (these 1s or 2s in the other rows conflict with the 1 or 2 in
     the given row and are therefore removed from B), and
   тАв all columns that have no 1s or 2s left are removed from B (these
     columns have a 1 or 2 in B and the constraint is therefore
     satisfied).
   The purpose of ┬п4 тОХDLX is:
   тАв To demonstrate how KnuthтАЩs algorithm works, and/or
   тАв To preset some initial values in B. For example, one can first
     initialize the constraints for an empty Sudoku (which is the same
     matrix for all Sudokus) and then enter the initial digits of a
     particular Sudoku using 4 тОХDLX. If there are, say, 20 initial
     digits in the Sudoku then A has 21 elements (┬п4 plus the 20 rows
     representing the 20 initial digits.  The result of ┬п4 тОХDLX B has
     the same number of rows as B (with some rows now cleared), but
     fewer columns than B.

   The right argument B of тОХDLX B or A тОХDLX B is a constraints matrix
whose columns consist of either 0s and 1s (called a primary column) or
0s and 2s (called secondary columns).  The 0s, 1s and 2s can be the
integers 0, 1, or 2, characters тАЩ0тАЩ, тАЩ1тАЩ, or тАЩ2тАЩ respectively, or тАЩ тАЩ
meaning тАЩ0тАЩ.  The character representation is useful when B becomes
large and shall be printed because the spaces in the numerical variant
will not be printed.  In the following, B is assumed to be numeric.

   Let ZтЖРA тОХDLX B, and let R be a solution in Z, that is, Z itself (A =
0) or R is Z[k] for some k if A тЙа 0.  And let SтЖР+тМ┐B[R].

   Then S = s1 s2 s3, ...  sN where N is the number of columns in B and
sj=1 if j is a primary column of B and sjтИИ0 1 if j is a secondary column
of B.

   In other words, тОХDLX B computes a subset of the rows of B in such a
way that for every column j of B exactly one (for primary column j) or
at most one (for a secondary column) of the rows in a solution has its
jтАЩth element set to 1 and all other words set their jтАЩth element set to
0.

   In yet other words, for every solution returned by тОХDLX B, a 1 in one
row prevents all other rows that also have a 1 in that column, and all
rows together have exactly one 1 in every primary column and at most one
1 in every secondary column.  In the absence of secondary columns, the
problem solved by тОХDLX is also known as the "exact cover problem"

   If all that sounds weird and useless, consider the following APL
program for finding all solutions of the 8 Queens problem on a chess
board (which probably every programmer has programmed at some point in
time):

           RCтЖР8тЖС'1' тЧК DтЖР15тЖС┬п8тЖС'2'   тНЭ helpers for constructing Q8
           тНЭ     rows   cols   diag1    diag2
           Q8тЖРтКГ{(RтМ╜RC),(CтМ╜RC),((C-R)тМ╜D),((┬п7-R+C)тМ╜D)тКг(R C)тЖР-8 8тКдтН╡-тОХIO} ┬и тН│64
           ZтЖР┬п1 тОХDLX Q8
           {тОХUCS (65+тМКтН╡├╖8)(49+8тИгтН╡тЖРтН╡-тОХIO)} ┬и тКГZ[1 2 3 92] тНЭ solutions 1, 2, 3, and 92
      A1 B5 C8 D6 G2 E3 F7 H4
      A1 B6 C8 D3 E7 F4 G2 H5
      A1 B7 C4 E8 D6 G5 F2 H3
      A8 B4 C1 D3 G7 E6 F2 H5

           8 8тН┤("+" "Q")[тОХIO+(тН│64)тИИтКГZ[1]]   тНЭ visualize solution Z[1]
     Q + + + + + + +
      + + + + Q + + +
      + + + + + + + Q
      + + + + + Q + +
      + + Q + + + + +
      + + + + + + Q +
      + Q + + + + + +
      + + + Q + + + +

   Obviously Z contains solutions for the 8 Queens problem; the total
number of solutions is well known to be 92 and we showed only the first
three and the last solution above.

   The constraint matrix Q8 is the key to success.  The matrix has 64
rows - one row for every field of the chess board.  And it has 8 + 8 +
15 + 15 columns.  The first 8 columns of Q8 are constraints that prevent
more than one Queen from being placed in the same row of the chess board
(the argument тН╡ is the field number counting from left to right and from
bottom to top).  The next 8 columns of Q8 are constraints that prevent
more than one Queen from being placed in the same column of the chess
board.

   If we would call тОХDLX with only these constraints, i.e.  тОХDLX T8тЖР64
