2.36.3 Plot Window Handling
---------------------------

Each call of тОХPLOT with some plot data B opens a separate window in the
X server (which implies that тОХPLOT requires X). That window runs in its
own thread until it is closed.  A plot window can be closed in different
ways:

   тАв interactively by clicking on the close button (often located near
     the top-right corner) of the plot window,
   тАв interactively by opening the drop down menu (if any) of the window
     (near the top left-of the window) and selecting the menu option
     named Close,
   тАв programmatically from APL by calling тОХPLOT ┬п3 (which closes all
     open plot windows), or
   тАв programmatically from APL by calling тОХPLOT H (which closes a
     specific plot window), where H is the plot window handle returned
     by monadic тОХPLOT B, or by dyadic A тОХPLOT B with plot attributes A
     and plot data B.

   Note that the exact method for closing a plot window interactively
with the mouse or the keyboard (as opposed to programmatically with
тОХPLOT ┬п3 or тОХPLOT H from APL) differs between different window managers.
The above corresponds to the typical method(s) for closing windows on
most systems.


File: apl.info,  Node: Output File Format,  Next: GUI driver,  Prev: Plot Window Handling,  Up: тОХPLOT - Plot Data

2.36.4 Output File Format
-------------------------

Early versions of тОХPLOT were using libxcb to display the results of
тОХPLOT while recent versions use libgtk-3.  The primary driver for this
change was the lack of full Unicode support in libxcb which made it, for
example, difficult to properly display APL characters in window captions
or in plot line legends.

   Writing the pixels of a plot to a file uses functions provided by
either libxcb or libgtk-3, and these functions generate different file
formats.

   libxcb is the older of the two libraries and it therefore produces
the older file format .bmp (bitmaps).  libgtk-3 is the newer library and
it produces the somewhat newer file format .png (portable network
graphics).  There are tools like convert from package imagemagick that
can be used to convert different image file formats into each other and
therefore this incompatibility should not cause too much trouble.

   For backward compatibility, the libxcb option for тОХPLOT will continue
to exist for some time, but bug fixes and new features will only be made
for the libgtk-3 option.


File: apl.info,  Node: GUI driver,  Prev: Output File Format,  Up: тОХPLOT - Plot Data

2.36.5 GUI driver
-----------------

тОХPLOT provides 3 different ways to generate its output, called GUI
drivers.  Two of these drivers (GTK and XCB) are optional, while third
third driver ASCII is not.  Optional means that the ./configure script,
which is executed as the first step in the compilation of GNU APL,
determines if the prerequisite for an optional driver are satisfied.
IOW an optional driver is only available for тОХPLOT if the libraries and
C/C++ header files needed to compile the driver are installed at the
time where GNU APL is being compiled.  The ASCII driver merely generates
ESC squences for VT100 terminals and does therefore not depend on
additional libraries.

   For the monadic тОХPLOT B, the driver used by тОХPLOT is chosen as
follows:

   тАв GTK if available, otherwise
   тАв XCB if available, otherwise
   тАв ASCII

   For the dyadic A тОХPLOT B, the driver used is the same, but the choice
made by ./configure can be overridden by the plot window attribute
gui_driver.  The default for this plot window attribute is empty, which
means that the decision of ./configure shall be used (like in the
monadic case where no plot attributes can be specified).

   The plot driver also affects the type of result returned by тОХPLOT:

   тАв drivers GTK and XCB return an integer scalar H (a plot window
     handle) that can later be used from APL to programmatically close
     the plot window (i.e.  with тОХPLOT H) with that handle.
     (Alternatively a GTK or XCB plot window can be closed by clicking
     the close button of the plot window).

   тАв driver ASCII returns a 3-dimensional APL value Z, where:
        тАв Z[1;;] is a character matrix with the Unicode characters used
          to draw the plot window,
        тАв Z[2;;] is an integer matrix with the the forground colors (in
          terms of VT100 terminal colors), and
        тАв Z[3;;] is an integer matrix with the the backround colors
          (again in terms of VT100 terminal colors).

   The VT100 colors returnd by the ASCII driver are essentially 4-bit
RGB values with the following integer encoding:

   тАв 0 = 0b000: (dark) black,
   тАв 1 = 0b001: (dark) red,
   тАв 2 = 0b010: (dark) green,
   тАв 3 = 0b011: (dark) yellow,
   тАв 4 = 0b100: (dark) blue,
   тАв 5 = 0b101: (dark) magenta,
   тАв 6 = 0b110: (dark) cyan,
   тАв 7 = 0b111: (dark) white (kind of grey),
   тАв 60 = 60 + 0b000: bright black (another kind of grey),
   тАв 61 = 60 + 0b001: bright red,
   тАв 62 = 60 + 0b010: bright green,
   тАв 63 = 60 + 0b011: bright yellow,
   тАв 64 = 60 + 0b100: bright blue,
   тАв 65 = 60 + 0b101: bright magenta,
   тАв 66 = 60 + 0b110: bright cyan, and
   тАв 67 = 60 + 0b111: bright white

   The ASCII driver returns its result as a committed value (so that the
plot window is not drawn twice if the value is not assigned to a
variable).  Naturally the ASCII driver can not support most of the тОХPLOT
atrributes like a true graphical driver like GTK or XCB. But at least
the color attributes are honored by rounding 3├Ч8-bit RGB values to their
nearest 4-bit VT100 color.

   Some terminal emulators have issues when characters are printed on
the last column of the terminal.  This is addressed by a user preference
named plot-ASCII-columns, which should be set to one less the number of
columns of the terminal (so that the last columns in not written).

   Another preferencefor the ASCII driver that might be of interest is
plot-ASCII-background.  It sets the background color for the terminal if
the Plot attribute canvas-color is not provided (e.g.  in monadic тОХPLOT
which has no plot attributes).

   The XCB driver was the first driver for тОХPLOT but has since become
somewhat obsolete.  It has limitation when it comes to the display of
texts (in particular for APL characters).  The long-term GNU APL design
strategy is therefore GTK in favor of the good old XCB. XCB will still
be supported for a while, but new features will only be added to the GTK
driver.


