2.40 тОХRVAL - Random APL value
=============================

The standard way to produce random numbers is the primitive function ?
aka.  Roll.  Roll returns a simple random array whose ravel elements are
positive integers chosen in a (pseudo-) random fashion.  While this is
sufficient for many applications, one sometimes needs APL values whose
randomness not only affects the ravel elements themselves, but also
other aspects like:

   тАв the rank of the value,
   тАв the shape of the value,
   тАв the data type of the ravel elements, and
   тАв the depth (nesting) of the values.

   Such values can be produced with system function тОХRVAL. The main use
case for тОХRVAL is the production of test data for the interpreter, but
тОХRVAL might be useful for other purposes as well.

* Menu:

* General::
* Dyadic тОХRVAL::


File: apl.info,  Node: General,  Next: Dyadic тОХRVAL,  Up: тОХRVAL - Random APL value

2.40.1 General
--------------

In general, monadic тОХRVAL B, returns a single random APL value Z, while
dyadic A RVAL B is used to control the properties of subsequently
generated random APL values returned by monadic тОХRVAL.

   The typical use of тОХRVAL is to first call A тОХRVAL B zero or more
times to override individual default properties of the subsequently
produced values, followed by one or more calls of monadic тОХRVAL B.

   The default properties, i.e.  the properties used unless they were
overridden by dyadic A тОХRVAL B, are:

     Rank:  0
     Shape: 1 1 1 1 1 1 1 1 (initially irrelevant since Rank = 0)
     Type:  0 1 0 0 0       (only integer random values)
     Max. Depth: 4          (initially irrelevant since type = 0 1 0 0 0)

   With these default properties, every call of monadic тОХRVAL B returns
an integer scalar.


File: apl.info,  Node: Dyadic тОХRVAL,  Prev: General,  Up: тОХRVAL - Random APL value

2.40.2 Dyadic тОХRVAL
-------------------

The left argument A of A тОХRVAL B determines which aspect of the
subsequent random APL values shall be controlled.  A is an integer
scalar:

   тАв A=0 controls the state of the underlying random number generator,

   тАв A=1 controls the ranks of the subsequent random APL values,

   тАв A=2 controls the shapes of the subsequent random APL values,

   тАв A=3 controls the data types in the ravels of the subsequent random
     APL values, and

   тАв A=4 controls a maximum depth of the subsequent random APL values.

* Menu:

* Control of the underlying random number generator: 0 тОХRVAL B::
* Control of the ranks: 1 тОХRVAL B::
* Control of the shapes: 2 тОХRVAL B::
* Control of the data types: 3 тОХRVAL B::
* Control of a maximum depth: 4 тОХRVAL B::
* monadic тОХRVAL B::
* Syntax Alternatives::


File: apl.info,  Node: Control of the underlying random number generator: 0 тОХRVAL B,  Next: Control of the ranks: 1 тОХRVAL B,  Up: Dyadic тОХRVAL

2.40.2.1 Control of the underlying random number generator: 0 тОХRVAL B
.....................................................................

Every random number generator has a state (similar to тОХRL for тАЩ?тАЩ).
While the primitive ?  keeps its state in тОХRL, i.e.  in the workspace,
тОХRVAL has no associated system variable like iтОХRL which keeps its state.
Instead, the user needs to store the state of iтОХRVAL in a workspace
variable if the workspace shall be stored and continued at a later
point.  This rarely happens, therefore no effort was spent on
implementing another system variable.  For the same reason does the
state of тОХRVAL survive )CLEAR.

   The current state of тОХRVALтАЩs random number generator can be retrieved
with:

           STATE тЖР 0 тОХRVAL ''

   The state changes with every call of monadic тОХRVAL. The random number
generator can later be restored to the same state like this:

           0 тОХRVAL STATE

   Restoring the state is needed when the same sequence of random values
shall be generated again.  The random number generators of ?  and тОХRVAL
are independent; generating a random number or random value with one
does not change the state of the other.


File: apl.info,  Node: Control of the ranks: 1 тОХRVAL B,  Next: Control of the shapes: 2 тОХRVAL B,  Prev: Control of the underlying random number generator: 0 тОХRVAL B,  Up: Dyadic тОХRVAL

2.40.2.2 Control of the ranks: 1 тОХRVAL B
........................................

The rank of subsequently generated random values can be controlled with
1 тОХRVAL B as follows:

   тАв If B is a non-negative scalar with 0 тЙд B < MAX_RANK then the
     subsequently generated random values will have the fixed rank B.
     MAX_RANK is a ./configurable constant with a default of 8.

   тАв If B is a negative scalar with 0 > B > -MAX_RANK then the ranks of
     the subsequently generated random values will be chosen at random
     between 0 and -B (inclusive).  All possible ranks 0 ...  B will
     have the same probability P = 100├╖1-B %.

   тАв Otherwise B must be a vector of positive integers.  The integers
     are the relative frequencies of the ranks 0, 1, ...  MAX_RANK
     respectively.  Too many integers (i.e.  MAX_RANK > тН┤B) will raise a
     LENGTH ERROR while fewer (than MAX_RANK) are set to 0.

   1 тОХRVAL always returns its previous setting (i.e.  before applying
B). An empty B, e.g.  1 тОХRVAL тНм will not change anything and can be used
to query the current setting for 1 тОХRVAL.

   Examples:

   тАв 1 тОХRVAL 2 will produce only matrices,

   тАв 1 тОХRVAL ┬п2 will produce scalars, vectors or matrices, each with a
     probability of 100├╖3 %, and

   тАв 1 тОХRVAL 50 30 20 will produce scalars with probability 50%, vectors
     with probability 30%, and matrices with probability 20%.  The
     numbers need not add up to 100, but will be scaled accordingly.


File: apl.info,  Node: Control of the shapes: 2 тОХRVAL B,  Next: Control of the data types: 3 тОХRVAL B,  Prev: Control of the ranks: 1 тОХRVAL B,  Up: Dyadic тОХRVAL

2.40.2.3 Control of the shapes: 2 тОХRVAL B
.........................................

The shapes of subsequently generated random values can be controlled
with 2 тОХRVAL B as follows.

   B must be a vector of positive or negative integers.  Vectors longer
than MAX_RANK + 1 will give a LENGTH ERROR while vectors shorter than
MAX_RANK + 1 will be filled with 1 until the length of B becomes
MAX_RANK + 1.

   If an element B_{i} of the resulting shape B = B_{1} ...  B_{MAXRANK}
is тЙе 0 then the corresponding axis i will have a fixed length of B_{i}.
If B_{i} < 0 then the length of that axis will be chosen at random with
a probability of 1├╖B_{i}.  Note that the same B can still produce
different shapes even if all B_{i} are тЙе 0 (i.e.  if the rank is also
chosen at random).

   2 тОХRVAL always returns its previous setting (i.e.  before applying
B). An empty B, e.g.  2 тОХRVAL тНм, will not change anything and can be
used to query the current setting for 2 тОХRVAL.

   Example:

     1 тОХRVAL 2        тНЭ produce matrices
     2 тОХRVAL 3 ┬п10    тНЭ the first axis of every matrix will have length 3, and
                      тНЭ the last axis of every matrix will vary between 0 and 10

   This will produce scalars, vectors with a fixed length of 3 and
matrices with 3 rows and between 0 and 10 columns.


File: apl.info,  Node: Control of the data types: 3 тОХRVAL B,  Next: Control of a maximum depth: 4 тОХRVAL B,  Prev: Control of the shapes: 2 тОХRVAL B,  Up: Dyadic тОХRVAL

2.40.2.4 Control of the data types: 3 тОХRVAL B
.............................................

The types (i.e.  CHARACTER, INTEGER, REAL, COMPLEX, or NESTED) of
subsequently generated random values can be controlled with 3 тОХRVAL B as
follows.

   B must be a vector with up to 5 positive numbers, corresponding to
the types.  Shorter vectors are filled with 0 (the corresponding types
will not occur) and longer vectors will raise a LENGTH error.

   Once the type was chosen, the ravel item will be:

   тАв for type CHARACTER: a random character with тОХUCS between 0 and
     $3000 (exclusive).  Larger Unicodes typically cause display
     problems.  If you need larger Unicodes, use тОХUCS with random
     integers.

   тАв for type INTEGER: a random integer with тОХUCS between -$80000000 and
     $7FFFFFFF.

   тАв for type REAL: a floating point number between 0.0 and 1.0
     (exclusive)

   тАв for type COMPLEX: a complex point number with real and imaginaty
     part between 0.0 and 1.0 (exclusive), and

   тАв for type NESTED: a nested APL value with the same properties (rank,
     shape, and type) as their parent.

   3 тОХRVAL always returns its previous setting (i.e.  before applying
B). An empty B, e.g.  3 тОХRVAL тНм will not change anything and can be used
to query the current setting for 3 тОХRVAL.

   Example:

           1 тОХRVAL 2         тНЭ produce matrices
           2 тОХRVAL 3 3       тНЭ produce 3├Ч3 matrices
           3 тОХRVAL 0 50 50   тНЭ produce a mix of integer and real values
           тОХRVAL 0
     ┬п975954163190248487                   0.5892132425
     7677327503669503253 2152001972871424768


File: apl.info,  Node: Control of a maximum depth: 4 тОХRVAL B,  Next: monadic тОХRVAL B,  Prev: Control of the data types: 3 тОХRVAL B,  Up: Dyadic тОХRVAL

2.40.2.5 Control of a maximum depth: 4 тОХRVAL B
..............................................

If the probability of generating a nested value is > 0 then the depth of
random values can become arbitrarily large and could therefore exceed
the system limit for the depth of the random value being produced.  This
can be prevented by setting a maximum depth for every value generated.
тОХRVAL sets the probability of the deepest allowed depth to 0.

   4 тОХRVAL B expects B to be a positive integer which is deepest allowed
depth;

   An empty B, e.g.  4 тОХRVAL тНм, will not change anything and can be used
to query the current setting for 4 тОХRVAL.


File: apl.info,  Node: monadic тОХRVAL B,  Next: Syntax Alternatives,  Prev: Control of a maximum depth: 4 тОХRVAL B,  Up: Dyadic тОХRVAL

2.40.2.6 monadic тОХRVAL B
........................

Calling тОХRVAL monadically either produces one new random APL value or
displays a list of arguments for dyadic тОХRVAL:

   тАв тОХRVAL тНм shows the valid left arguments of A тОХRVAL B with a brief
     description,
   тАв тОХRVAL тАЭ shows the valid syntaces of A тОХRVAL B (see also *Note
     Function Groups::.
   тАв тОХRVAL 0 returns the next random value according to the properties
     set with dyadic тОХRVAL.

   The properties of that next value can be controlled by the dyadic
calls of тОХRVAL as described above.  If no prior dyadic call of тОХRVAL was
made then the properties have the following defaults:

           1 тОХRVAL тНм    тНЭ rank (scalar)
     0

           2 тОХRVAL тНм    тНЭ shape (not used since rank = 0)
     1 1 1 1 1 1 1 1

           3 тОХRVAL тНм    тНЭ types (integer)
     0 1 0 0 0

           4 тОХRVAL тНм    тНЭ max. depth (not used since probability of NESTED = 0)
     4

   That is, by default, тОХRVAL тНм produces random integer scalars.

   It is sometimes convenient to be able to change the properties of the
next random value without modifying (and later restoring) the properties
with dyadic тОХRVAL. This can be achieved with monadic тОХRVAL with
non-empty B.

   Let 4=тН┤B. Then

        ZтЖРтОХRVAL B does essentially:

        B[1]тЖР1 тОХRVAL B[1]
        B[2]тЖР2 тОХRVAL B[2]
        B[3]тЖР3 тОХRVAL B[3]
        B[4]тЖР4 тОХRVAL B[4]

        ZтЖРтОХRVAL 0

        B[1]тЖР1 тОХRVAL B[1]
        B[2]тЖР2 тОХRVAL B[2]
        B[3]тЖР3 тОХRVAL B[3]
        B[4]тЖР4 тОХRVAL B[4]

   If 4 > тН┤B then the missing properties are not changed.

   Examples:

     тОХRVAL 1 (,┬п4) (0 1)    тНЭ return a random 0-4 element integer vector
     тОХRVAL 2 (2 2) (1 0)    тНЭ return a random 2├Ч2 character array


File: apl.info,  Node: Syntax Alternatives,  Prev: monadic тОХRVAL B,  Up: Dyadic тОХRVAL

2.40.2.7 Syntax Alternatives
............................

For an improved readability, тОХRVAL also accepts string arguments for its
left argument A and also the sub-function notation:

           0 тОХRVAL B  тЖРтЖТ  'state' тОХRVAL B  тЖРтЖТ  тОХRVAL.state B
           1 тОХRVAL B  тЖРтЖТ   'rank' тОХRVAL B  тЖРтЖТ  тОХRVAL.rank  B
           2 тОХRVAL B  тЖРтЖТ  'shape' тОХRVAL B  тЖРтЖТ  тОХRVAL.shape B
           3 тОХRVAL B  тЖРтЖТ   'type' тОХRVAL B  тЖРтЖТ  тОХRVAL.type  B
           4 тОХRVAL B  тЖРтЖТ  'depth' тОХRVAL B  тЖРтЖТ  тОХRVAL.depth B


