2.41 тОХSI - State Indicator
==========================

тОХSI returns aspects of the current State Indicator, similar to the
standard command )SI. This can be used, for example, to create debug
functions similar to the assert() macro in C/C++:

     тИЗAssert B;COND;LOC;VAR
      тЖТ(1тЙбB)тН┤0
      ' '
      CONDтЖР7тЖУ,┬п2 тОХSI 4
      LOCтЖР,┬п2 тОХSI 3
      '************************************************'
      ' '
      '*** Assertion (', COND, ') failed at ',LOC
      ''

      тНЭ show stack
      тНЭ
      ' '
      'Stack:'
      7 тОХCR тКГ┬п1тЖУтОХSI 3
      ' '
      '************************************************</pre>'
      тЖТ
     тИЗ

   The right argument of тОХSI specifies which aspect of the State
Indicator shall be returned:

   тАв тОХSI 1: The name of the context.  That name is either:
        тАв the name of a defined function, or
        тАв тЧК for an immediate execution context, or
        тАв тНО for an execute context.

   тАв тОХSI 2: The line number (of a defined function) or 0 for immediate
     execution and execute contexts.

   тАв тОХSI 3: The function name and line number in square brackets, for
     example: "FOO[3]"

   тАв тОХSI 4: Either the statement text of the function line or the error
     text of an error that has occurred on the line

   тАв тОХSI 5: The program counter (= token number counted from the start
     of the function text)

   тАв тОХSI 6: the parse mode of the context (immediate execution, execute,
     or defined function).

   If no left argument is provided then the result of тОХSI is a vector
with one entry per State Indicator level (and hence тН┤тОХSI B is the depth
of the SI stack).

   If the optional left argument A is provided then it specifies a
particular level of the SI instead of the entire SI. A should be an
integer scalar.  If A is positive then the level is counted from the
oldest entry to the latest, while negative A counts from the latest to
the oldest level.

   For example, ┬п1 тОХSI refers to the currently executing context, ┬п2 тОХSI
is the caller, and so on.


File: apl.info,  Node: тОХSQL - SQL Database Interface,  Next: тОХSYL - System limits,  Prev: тОХSI - State Indicator,  Up: Non-standard GNU APL Features

2.42 тОХSQL - SQL Database Interface
==================================

тОХSQL was kindly contributed by Elias M├еrtenson.

   As of GNU APL 1.6, the native function SQL has been replaced by the
system function тОХSQL, described below.  тОХSQL has an axis argument that
selects a sub-function of тОХSQL.

* Menu:

* тОХSQL[0] тНм : display sub-function numbers::
* тОХSQL[0] '' : display sub-function names::
* ref тЖР A тОХSQL[1] B : open database::
* тОХSQL[2] B : close database::
* Z тЖР A тОХSQL[3 ref] B : database query (with result)::
* Z тЖР A тОХSQL[4 ref] B : database query (w/o result)::
* тОХSQL[5] B : start transaction::
* тОХSQL[6] B : commit transaction::
* тОХSQL[7] B : rollback transaction::
* ZтЖРтОХSQL[8] B : table names::
