2.42.14.1 Deleting a Database
.............................

In order to have a well-defined starting point we delete any already
existing database.  In SQLite every database is contained in a single
file, frequently named db.sqlite.

   CAUTION: The тОХFIO.unlink command below will erase any existing
database without a warning.

           )CLEAR
     CLEAR WS

           тНЭ delete any existing database
           тНЭ
           Filename тЖР "db.sqlite"                тНЭ name of the database to be deleted
           тОХFIO.strerror тОХFIO.unlink Filename
     Success

           тНЭ verify that it was deleted
           тНЭ
           тОХFIO.strerror тОХFIO.unlink Filename
     No such file or directory

   NOTES: An SQLite database can be closed in two ways: using
тОХFIO.unlink as shown above, or with an SQL query such as "DROP DATABASE
IF EXISTS db.sqlite".  However, to issue an SQL query we would need to
create an SQL connection to a database that we do not yet have at this
point.

   For databases that are more complex than SQLite, an SQL query or a
utility program shipped with the database might be required.  For
example, postgreSQL comes with a program named dropdb that deletes a
database.  Such programs can be called from APL with the )HOST command
or with тОХFIO.fork_daemon.


File: apl.info,  Node: Creating a new Database,  Next: Creating a Database Table,  Prev: Deleting a Database,  Up: SQLite Quickstart

2.42.14.2 Creating a new Database
.................................

To read from or write into a database we need a database handle
(sometimes called a database connection) for it:

           )CLEAR
     CLEAR WS

           тНЭ create a new (and empty) database
           тНЭ
           Filename тЖР 'db.sqlite'            тНЭ name of the database to be created
           Type тЖР 'sqlite'                   тНЭ database type
           DB тЖР Type тОХSQL.open Filename      тНЭ create the database

           тОХSQL.close DB                     тНЭ and close it

   NOTES: If a file with the given Filename already exists, then
тОХSQL.open simply connects to it and returns a handle (a small integer)
for the connection.  The handle is used like a file descri[tor for an
open file in the operating system.  The handle is later used for
subsequent database operations of тОХSQL (until the connection is closed).

   If no file with the given Filename exists, then тОХSQL.open creates a
file with than name and then connects to it.  It is possible to have
several such connections to different databases at the same time.  It is
also possible to have several connections to the same database at the
same time (and then one should use database transactions to avoid
conflicts with the data written to the same database via different
connections).

   postgreSQL is shipped with programs createdb for creating databases,
createuser for creating database users, and psql for various other
database administration tasks.  These programs can be called from APL
with the )HOST command or with тОХFIO.fork_daemon.


File: apl.info,  Node: Creating a Database Table,  Next: Excursus: Dynamic Query Strings,  Prev: Creating a new Database,  Up: SQLite Quickstart

2.42.14.3 Creating a Database Table
...................................

An SQL database is a set of tables.  The next step after a new database
was created and a connection to it was opened is to define one or more
tables in the database.  Every table has one or more named columns and
zero or more rows.  Every column has attributes, some of which are
mandatory (e.g.  the column name and in some SQL dialects the data type)
while others are optional (e.g.  the data type in other SQL dialects or
the size of the items in the column).  Creating a database table means
to specify a name for a table and to specify the attributes of the table
columns.

   In this quickstart we create a table named EMPLOYEES with 5 columns
named ID, NAME, ADDRESS, AGE, and SALARY.

           )CLEAR
     CLEAR WS

           Filename тЖР 'db.sqlite'            тНЭ name of the database to be used
           Type тЖР 'sqlite'                   тНЭ database type
           DB тЖР Type тОХSQL.open Filename      тНЭ open the database

           тНЭ define an SQL Query string Qs that creates a table
           тНЭ
           Qs тЖР ,тКГ┬л┬л┬л
           CREATE TABLE EMPLOYEES(
                  ID      INT  NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY,
                  NAME    TEXT NOT NULL,
                  AGE     INT  NOT NULL,
                  ADDRESS CHAR(50),
                  SALARY  REAL);
                  ┬╗┬╗┬╗

           тНЭ perform the SQL query according to query string Qs.
           тНЭ
           Qs тОХSQL.query DB тНм

           тНЭ show the tables in the database
           тНЭ
           тОХSQL.tables DB
      EMPLOYEES

           DB тОХSQL.columns 'EMPLOYEES'
      ID      INT
      NAME    TEXT
      AGE     INT
      ADDRESS CHAR(50)
      SALARY  REAL

           тОХSQL.close DB                     тНЭ and close DB

   NOTES: As we see above, SQL query strings tend to be quite long.  We
could have removed most of the blanks and all of the linefeeds in the
query string above, but readability of the SQL query would have suffered
a lot by doing that.  Instead we used a multi-line GNU APL script ┬л┬л┬л
...  ┬╗┬╗┬╗ for the query text, disclose it (which turns the APL vector of
strings into an APL matrix, and finally ravel it (to make it a string).

   Many SQL query strings contain strings themselves, e.g.  for column
names that contain blanks or for string values in columns.  IOW, the
query string is a string that contains other strings.  To avoid the need
to escape the SQL quotes inside (quoted) APL strings we have quoted the
multi-line query string with ┬л┬л┬л ...  ┬╗┬╗┬╗ instead of """ ...  """  or тАЭтАЩ
...  тАЭтАЩ.

   The right argument of тОХSQL.query is DB тНм (and not simply DB as in
other тОХSQL functions).  This is because an SQL query string can have
parameters as we will see below.  The query string above has no
parameters and therefore the parameter list for the query string is тНм
aka.  тН│0.

   Finally, SQL table columns have names, but SQL table rows do not.  It
is therefore common practice (though not required) that the first column
of a table is a unique integer ID that identifies the row and can later
be used to quickly locate the row in a large database.


File: apl.info,  Node: Excursus: Dynamic Query Strings,  Next: Writing an APL matrix into a Database Table,  Prev: Creating a Database Table,  Up: SQLite Quickstart

2.42.14.4 Excursus: Dynamic Query Strings
.........................................

The SQL query strings (Qs) used so far were static, which means that
they are sent verbatim to the database machinery.  In the following we
will also use SQL query strings that are are a mix of static text and
the character % in the query string.  In other SQL dialects the
placeholders may be different.  For example in postgreSQL the
placeholders in a query string are $1, $2, $3, and so forth.

   The placeholders in a dynamic query string are replaced by string is
to the database machinery.  For example:

           тНЭ dynamic query string Qs
           тНЭ
           Qs тЖР ,тКГ┬л┬л┬л
           INSERT INTO EMPLOYEES(ID, NAME, AGE, ADDRESS, SALARY
                    VALUES(?,  ?,    ?,   ?,       ?);
                ┬╗┬╗┬╗

           тНЭ query string parameters
           тНЭ
           PARAMS тЖР 1 "Paul" 32 "California" 20000

           тНЭ number of placeholders in Qs
           тНЭ
           +/Qs = '?'
     5

           тНЭ number of parameters (shall be equal to the number of placeholders)
           тНЭ
           тН┤PARAMS
     5

           тНЭ the (intermediate) result of replacing the placeholders in the dynamic
           тНЭ query string Qs would then be this static query string:
           тНЭ
           RESULT тЖР ,тКГ┬л┬л┬л
           INSERT INTO EMPLOYEES(ID, NAME, AGE, ADDRESS, SALARY
                    VALUES(1, "Paul", 32, "California", 20000);
                      ┬╗┬╗┬╗

   The example above shows the binding of query string parameters to
query strings for the case where the rank of the parameters is тЙд 1.
тОХSQL also supports parameters with rank 2; in that case the query is
repeated for every row of the parameter matrix.  I.e.  the placeholders
in same query string Qs are being replaced with every row of the
parameter matrix before the result of each replacement is sent as a
(static) query to the database machinery.  This feature makes it rather
simple to write an APL matrix (= query parameter) to the database.

   Dynamic query strings are allowed in two тОХSQL sub-functions: in
function 3 (тОХSQL.query) and in function 4 (тОХSQL.update).  The syntax
differs slightly beween тОХSQL function numbers and тОХSQL function names:

           Qs тОХSQL.query DB PARAMS       тНЭ тОХSQL sub-function name
           Qs тОХSQL[3, DB] PARAMS         тНЭ тОХSQL sub-function number

           Qs тОХSQL.update DB PARAMS      тНЭ тОХSQL sub-function name
           Qs тОХSQL[4, DB] PARAMS         тНЭ тОХSQL sub-function number

   For rank 2 parameters shall the number of placeholders be equal to
the number of colums of the APL matrix.  If a query string contains no
placeholders then the parameters shall be тНм (aka.  тН│0).


File: apl.info,  Node: Writing an APL matrix into a Database Table,  Next: Reading a Database Table into an APL Matrix,  Prev: Excursus: Dynamic Query Strings,  Up: SQLite Quickstart

2.42.14.5 Writing an APL matrix into a Database Table
.....................................................

Now suppose that we have an APL matrix with the same columns as our SQL
