     тФВтФФтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФШ     тФФтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФШ          тФВ
     тФВтФМтЖТтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФР 26 тФМтЖТтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФР     18000тФВ
     тФВтФВGunnarтФВ    тФВSwedenтФВ          тФВ
     тФВтФФтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФШ    тФФтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФШ          тФВ
     тФФ╧╡тФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФШ

   This MATRIX can then be written (more precisely: appended) to the
database table EMPLOYEES like this:

           )CLEAR
     CLEAR WS

           Filename тЖР 'db.sqlite'            тНЭ name of the database to be used
           Type тЖР 'sqlite'                   тНЭ database type
           DB тЖР Type тОХSQL.open Filename      тНЭ open the database

           Qs тЖР ,тКГ┬л┬л┬л
           INSERT INTO EMPLOYEES(ID, NAME, AGE, ADDRESS, SALARY)
                          VALUES(?,  ?,    ?,   ?,       ?);
                ┬╗┬╗┬╗
          Qs тОХSQL.query DB MATRIX

           тОХSQL.close DB                     тНЭ and close DB


File: apl.info,  Node: Reading a Database Table into an APL Matrix,  Next: Updating a Database Table,  Prev: Writing an APL matrix into a Database Table,  Up: SQLite Quickstart

2.42.14.6 Reading a Database Table into an APL Matrix
.....................................................

Reading a matrix back from a database table uses a SELECT query.  SELECT
is the counterpart of indexed reference or indexed assignment in APL and
works, like in APL, in both directions (i.e.  reading from tables and
writing to tables).  In a SELECT query one can select specific rows and
columns of the table, which is left as an exercise for the reader.  In
this quickstart we want to keep things simple and read an entire table
back:

   Due to the absence of a binding mechanism is reading back of an SQL
table into an APL matrix even simpler:

           )CLEAR
     CLEAR WS

           Filename тЖР 'db.sqlite'            тНЭ name of the database to be used
           Type тЖР 'sqlite'                   тНЭ database type
           DB тЖР Type тОХSQL.open Filename      тНЭ open the database

           Qs тЖР ,тКГ┬л┬л┬л
           SELECT * FROM EMPLOYEES;
                  ┬╗┬╗┬╗

           RESULT тЖР Qs тОХSQL.query DB тНм
           RESULT
      1 Paul   32 California 20000
      2 Allan  25 Texas      15000
      3 Teddy  23 Norway     20000
      4 Gunnar 26 Sweden     18000

           тН┤RESULT
     4 5

           тОХSQL.close DB                     тНЭ and close DB

   NOTES: The * in the query string stands for all columns of the table.
* is NOT a placeholder because it is not replaced with a parameter.  One
can also retrieve a only subset of columns by using a comma separated
list of column names instead of * (similar to indexed reference in APL).


File: apl.info,  Node: Updating a Database Table,  Prev: Reading a Database Table into an APL Matrix,  Up: SQLite Quickstart

2.42.14.7 Updating a Database Table
...................................

The тОХSQL sub-function introduced so far suffice, at least in principle.
The APL programmer can read a table from the database into APL, analyse
and/or modify it in APL, and optionally write it back into the database.

   There is, however, one case where this approach becomes arbitrarily
inefficient: a large database with only a small change.  In that case it
is far more efficient to make a change directly in the database, i.e.
without transferring the entire database back and forth between APL and
SQL. This is achieved with an SQL UPDATE query, and тОХSQL.update does
exactly that.

   Suppose we want to increase TeddyтАЩs salary from 20000 to 22000.
Then:

           )CLEAR
     CLEAR WS

           Filename тЖР 'db.sqlite'            тНЭ name of the database to be used
           Type тЖР 'sqlite'                   тНЭ database type
           DB тЖР Type тОХSQL.open Filename      тНЭ open the database

           Qs тЖР ,тКГ┬л┬л┬л
           UPDATE EMPLOYEES SET SALARY=? WHERE ID=?;
                  ┬╗┬╗┬╗

           Qs тОХSQL.query DB (22000 3)        тНЭ update column SALARY in row 3

           тНЭ check result
           Qs тЖР ,тКГ┬л┬л┬л
           SELECT * FROM EMPLOYEES;
                  ┬╗┬╗┬╗

           RESULT тЖР Qs тОХSQL.query DB тНм
           RESULT
      1 Paul   32 California 20000
      2 Allan  25 Texas      15000
      3 Teddy  23 Norway     22000
      4 Gunnar 26 Sweden     18000

           тН┤RESULT
     4 5

           тОХSQL.close DB                     тНЭ and close DB

   NOTES: an UPDATE query in SQL is pretty much what an indexed
assignment in APL. In the example above we changed a single column
SALARY in a single row ID in the database table COMPANY. The placeholder
% in SET SALARY=% was set to parameter 22000 and the place holder in
where ID=?  was set to TerryтАЩs row with ID. Like in APL one can,
however, also change multiple rows and/or multiple columns in a database
table.  To change multiple columns one can set a comma separated list of
column names in the SET clause (or * for all columns).  For multiple
rows one can set multiple rows in the WHERE clause.  Omitting the WHERE
clause updates all rows (similar to * for columns) in the database.  For
example:

           UPDATE COMPANY SET AGE=?, SALARY=? WHERE ID IN (?, ?, ?);

   The shape of a parameter matrix for an SQL UPDATE must, of course,
match the number of selected rows and columns.


File: apl.info,  Node: Deleting Rows From a Database Table,  Prev: SQLite Quickstart,  Up: тОХSQL - SQL Database Interface

2.42.15 Deleting Rows From a Database Table
-------------------------------------------

Like UPDATE queries are efficient for changing large tables of a
database, there is also an SQL query for deleting one or more rows of a
database:

           QsтЖР┬лDELETE FROM COMPANY WHERE ID=?;┬╗                тНЭ delete one row
           QsтЖР┬лDELETE FROM COMPANY WHERE ID IN (?, ?, ?);┬╗     тНЭ delete 3 rows
           QsтЖР┬лDELETE FROM COMPANY;┬╗                           тНЭ delete all (!) rows

           Qs тОХSQL.query DB B

   As usual, the number of rows must match the number of placeholders in
the query parameter B (an APL vector).


