2.44.1 Purpose
--------------

GNU APL provides тОХXML as a means of performing elementary manipulations
of APL character strings that are formatted according to the XML
standard.  The anticipated procedure for such modifications is something
like:

           XML_string тЖР "<A><B><C>Hello</C></B></A>"   тНЭ input data (usually from an .xml file)
           APL тЖР тОХXML XML_string       тНЭ convert XML_string to associative array APL
           ABC тЖР APL.a.b.c             тНЭ retrieve node a.b.c in APL
           APL.a.b.c тЖР ABC, " World"   тНЭ modify node a.b.c in APL
           Z тЖР тОХXML APL                тНЭ convert associative array APL to XML string Z

           ABC   тНЭ the original value of XML.a.b.c
     Hello
           Z     тНЭ the modified XML string
     <A><B><C>Hello World</C></B></A>"

   The scope (functionality) of тОХXML is then:

   тАв Conversion of (valid) XML strings to associative APL arrays that
     can be more easily processed in APL than the XML strings,
   тАв Conversion of associative APL arrays back to valid XML strings,
   тАв Simple (at APL level) access to the data contained in XML strings,
     and
   тАв Transparent access to those (mostly XML specific) portions of the
     XML string that are not (yet) handled by тОХXML; this means that the
     user of тОХXML shall be able to handle advanced XML aspects (like
     document type declarations (DTDs), document validation, etc.)  in
     APL without much overhead.


File: apl.info,  Node: Some XML Terminology,  Next: How тОХXML maps XML documents to APL Values,  Prev: Purpose,  Up: тОХXML - XML Parsing

2.44.2 Some XML Terminology
---------------------------

An XML document is a character string with a standardized format.  The
characters must be valid XML characters as defined in the XML standard
(almost all Unicode characters except most of the ASCII control
characters).  GNU APL raises a DOMAIN ERROR when an XML document
contains invalid XML characters.

   The XML document is a sequence of adjacent sub-strings, where each
sub-string is:

   тАв either markup (-string),
   тАв or non-markup (-string).

   A markup (sub-)string:

   тАв starts with character тАЩ<тАЩ, and
   тАв ends with character тАЩ>тАЩ, and
   тАв all other characters in the markup string differ from тАЩ<тАЩ and тАЩ>тАЩ.

   A non-markup (sub-)string:

   тАв starts either at the beginning of the XML document or else directly
     after a markup string,
   тАв end at the end of the document or else directly before a markup
     string, and therefore
   тАв cannot be adjacent to another non-markup string.

   Non-markup is sometimes referred to as "unstructured text".  The
producer of an XML document has a principal choice about where to locate
the information that the document contains: in the unstructured text or
in the attribute values inside the tags.  For that reason the XML
standard is somewhat picky about keeping the unstructured text as well
as attribute values intact and requires that whitespace in non-markup
(the only allowed whitespace characters in XML being TAB, CR, LF, and
SPACE) is preserved in non-markup strings.

   As a consequence, many non-markup strings begin with LF because the
preceeding markup was on the previous line and therefore the LF after
the preceeding markup is whitespace of the non-markup and therefore
needs to be preserved.

   Every markup belongs to one of 4 categories:

   тАв Processing instructions: "<?  ...  ?>",
   тАв Comments: "<!тАФ ...  тАФ>",
   тАв Declarations "<!  ...  !>", and
   тАв Tags, which are either:
        тАв Empty tags (leaf tags): "<tagname attributes...  />
        тАв Start tags: "<tagname attributes...  >, or
        тАв End tags: "</tagname>

   The XML tags recursively define a tree structure where:

   тАв the nodes of the trees are either Empty Tags or else a start tag,
     followed by a (possibly empty) sequence of non-markup, comments,
     and sub-nodes (of the tree), followed by an end tag (with the same
     name as the start tag),
   тАв the leafs of the trees are either Empty Tags or else a start tag,
     followed by a (possibly empty) sequence of non-markup and comments,
     followed by an end tag (with the same name as the start tag).  The
     difference between a leaf node and a non-leaf is therefore the
     absence of sub-nodes between a start and an end tag.
   тАв optionally non-markup and comments before, after, and between the
     nodes.

   Processing instructions and declarations are typically located at the
beginning of the XML document and at the same level as the root of the
tree defined by the document.  Document type declarations are preserved
(so that they can be processed in APL), but are currently ignored by
тОХXML. As a consequence, entity declarations have no effect and only the
predefined XML entities (i.e.  &, <, >, тАЩ, and ") are recognized (and
translated) by тОХXML.


File: apl.info,  Node: How тОХXML maps XML documents to APL Values,  Next: Monadic тОХXML,  Prev: Some XML Terminology,  Up: тОХXML - XML Parsing

2.44.3 How тОХXML maps XML documents to APL Values
------------------------------------------------

The principal mapping between XML strings and APL values is:

   тАв XML document тЖРтЖТ structured (top-level) APL value or variable (= an
     associative array)
   тАв XML node тЖРтЖТ structured APL (sub-) value (= an associative (sub-)
     array of either the top-level value or of another XML node)
   тАв XML name тЖРтЖТ name of a member in a structured APL value
   тАв Other тЖРтЖТ member value

   Every valid name in XML is also a valid name for an APL variable or
structure member.  Unfortunately, mapping XML names directly to APL
member names cannot work because:

   тАв In any associative array the names of the members are necessarily
     distinct.  Assigning a value to an already existing member of a
     structured value overwrites the current value of that member
     instead of creating a second member with that value.  On the other
     hand, in XML nodes tags may (and frequently do) occur repeatedly.
     If an XML document contains several nodes with the same tag, then
     the applications usually knows how to interpret the order in which
     the tags occur, but this order may not be detectable at the XML
     level (i.e.  the nodes may not only have the same tag names, but
     also the same attributes and attribute values).

     The applications that use the XML document frequently require that
     the order of XML nodes with the same name remain intact when the
     document is modified.  For example, the entries of a telephone book
     may be sorted alphabetically without XML being aware of that.
     Reading, modifying, and writing back the data in the telephone book
     must therefore not destroy that order.

   тАв Likewise, at least for readability reasons, the order of node
     attributes should not be changed.  XML documents are frequently
     processed with text tools like diff which would incorrectly show
     differences between XML documents that are equivalent from an XML
     perspective.

   тАв Conflicts between tag names and attribute names.  In XML, the same
     name can designate an attribute in one node and a tag in another
     node.  тОХXML keeps all information from the < of a start tag to the
     > of an end tag in a single associative array, therefore the
     attribute names must somehow differ from the (sub-) tag names.

   тАв Every XML node has a tag name that can be used to derive a
     corresponding APL member name.  However, the text segments between
     an XML tag and its corresponding end tag, are a mixture of
     unstructured text, XML subnodes and comments of which only the XML
     subnodes have tags of their own.  These untagged segments may,
     however, contain relevant information and, from an XML standard
     perspective, both their content and their order must be preserved.

   тОХXML solves these issues with a simple naming convention for all
member names in the (recursive) associative array that is produced by
monadic тОХXML. Every member name consists of 3 components that together
yield a valid APL variable name (and therefore a valid member name that
is understood by the APL parser):

   тАв A single character тНЩ, тИЖ, or _, that indicates the role of the name
     in the XML document as follows:
        тАв the character тНЩ characterizes an attribute name, i.e.  a name
          that was used inside (i.e.  between < and >) of an XML start
          or leaf tag.  The character тНЩ alone is the name of a special
          member which is present in every associative array below the
          top-level and whose value is the original XML tag name of a
          tag, or

        тАв the character тИЖ characterizes a name that was synthesized by
          тОХXML itself to tag a text (sub-) segment that has no tag of
          its own.  The corresponding XML entity was not a tag (and
          therefore had no tag name), or

        тАв the character _ characterizes the name of an XML entity, i.e.
          a CML name that occurred between the start tag and the
          corresponding end tag (if any: leaf tags have no such
          entities)

   тАв a position prefix of the form NN, where NN is the position of the
     member in relation to the tag to which it belongs.  The numbering
     starts at тОХIO and restarts at every XML start or leaf tag.

   тАв the attribute name or tag name.  For those parts of an XML entity
     that do not have a tag name, the member name is synthesized by тОХXML
     and the member value will be the text in the XML document with
     predefined XML entities replaced by their single characters, i.e.:
        тАв & for &amp,
        тАв < for &lt,
        тАв > for &gt,
        тАв тАЩ for &apos,
        тАв " for &quot,
        тАв тОХUCS nnn for &#nnn, and
        тАв тОХUCS $xxx for &#xxx

   Let NN be a sequence of decimal digits.  Then only the following 4
synthesized names are produced by тОХXML:

   тАв тИЖNNcomment for XML comments, i.e.  <!тАФ ...  тАФ> in XML,
   тАв тИЖNNdeclaration for XML declarations, i.e.  <?  ...  ?> in XML,
   тАв тИЖNNdoctype for document type declarations, i.e.  <!DOCTYPE ...  >
     in XML
   тАв тИЖNNtext for unstructured (and hence untagged) text segments in XML.

   Every XML name (of a tag or attribute) is also a valid APL name, but
valid APL names may also contain the characters _, тИЖ, and тНЩ which are
not valid in XML and used in the naming convention above to clearly
separate the member names used in APL from the names used in the XML
document.

   The essence of all this is that everything that belongs to an XML
node or document, i.e.  the attributes inside a tag, the sub-nodes
between a start tag and its corresponding end tag (if any),
declarations, etc.  will be contained in a single associative array.

   Examples of APL member names (assuming тОХIOтЖР1):

           тНЩ1              тНЭ the first member in every XML node. Its value is the node tag.
           тИЖ1declaration   тНЭ the first member in most XML documents. E.g. <?xml version= ...>
           тИЖ2text          тНЭ whitespace (LF) between _1тИЖdeclaration and _3тИЖdoctype
           тИЖ3doctype       тНЭ DTD in XML documents that have one. E.g. <!DOCTYPE  ...
           _6Workspace     тНЭ Sub-array for <Workspace ... at position 6.
           тНЩ1wsid          тНЭ first attribute wsid from e.g. <Workspace wsid=...
           тНЩ2year          тНЭ second attribute year


File: apl.info,  Node: Monadic тОХXML,  Next: Dyadic тОХXML,  Prev: How тОХXML maps XML documents to APL Values,  Up: тОХXML - XML Parsing

2.44.4 Monadic тОХXML
-------------------

Z тЖР тОХXML B converts APL string B that contains a valid XML document to
an associative APL array Z and vice versa.

   Note: If you convert an associative APL array back to a an XML
document, the result is a possibly very long string containing several
linefeed characters.  That is OK if the string is written to a file, but
causes problems when the string is displayed and longer than тОХPW. The
standard APL folding of output near тОХPW make the string then look
somewhat garbled.  This effect can be suppressed in 2 ways:

  1. set тОХPW large enough, or
  2. prefix the string with тКГ35тОХCR as in the examples below.


File: apl.info,  Node: Dyadic тОХXML,  Next: XML Queries,  Prev: Monadic тОХXML,  Up: тОХXML - XML Parsing

2.44.5 Dyadic тОХXML
------------------

Z тЖР A тОХXML B provides a number of convenience functions.  Its left
argument A is an integer function number, possibly followed by arguments
of the function number тЖСA.

   In the following examples, let

           XMLтЖР36 тОХCR """
     <?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
       <Document>
         <Tag1 name='tag1'>   <!-- first tag -->
           TEXT1
           <Subtag name='subag1.1'>   <!-- first subtag -->
             SUBTEXT1_1
           </Subtag>
         </Tag1>
       </Document>
     """

     APLтЖРтОХXML XML

   Then

   тАв ZтЖР0 тОХXML B is the same as monadic ZтЖРтОХXML B.

   тАв ZтЖР1 тОХXML B is like 0 тОХXML B, except that B is not the XML document
     (string) itself but the name of a file from which an XML document
     is read.

   тАв ZтЖР2 тОХXML B splits an APL member path (a sequence of member names)
     into a vector P of (nested) member names.  This vector P is
     understood by the APL primitive PICK (i.e.  ZтЖРPтКГAPL or
     (PтКГAPL)тЖРvalue and can be used to address the data in an XML node.

   тАв ZтЖР3 тОХXML B splits an APL member name (as produced by e.g.  monadic
     тОХXML into a 3-item vector Z. Z[1] is a single character indicating
     the category (i.e.  a character scalar тИЖ, тНЩ, or _).  Z[2] is the
