2.45.2 Syntax
-------------

With the above considerations in mind, GNU APL decided in favor of the
following syntax for APL conditionals:

   тАв one-sided if/else:
                COND тЖТтЖТ THEN-statement(s) тЖРтЖР

   тАв two-sided if/else:
                COND тЖТтЖТ THEN-statement(s) тЖРтЖТ ELSE-statement(s) тЖРтЖР

   The following rules govern this syntax:

   тАв The тЖТтЖТ, тЖРтЖТ, and тЖРтЖР markers must be single tokens (2 adjacent
     Unicode characters).  No whitespace (and in particular no line
     feed) is permitted between the first and the second arrow.  A
     single тЖТ is a valid APL statement (named Escape).  A linefeed
     between two тЖТ turns the single token тЖТтЖТ into two valid (though most
     of the time useless) Escape statements.

   тАв The COND, THEN, and ELSE clauses shall be sequences of valid APL
     statements.  In particular:
        тАв The condition COND shall be a single statement that evaluates
          to a 1-item Boolean array (of any rank).  The statement result
          of COND is a committed value and is therefore not being
          displayed.

        тАв The THEN clause shall be one or more valid statements,
          possibly separated by тЧК for more than one statement.

        тАв Likewise, the ELSE clause (if present) shall be one or more
          valid statements, separated by тЧК for more than one statement.

   Examples:
           тНЭ short format. Valid in immediate execution and in defined functions
           тНЭ
           XтЖР5 тЧК XтЙе0 тЖТтЖТ X 'is positive' тЖРтЖТ X 'is negative' тЖРтЖР
      5 is positive


           тНЭ long format. Only possible in defined functions because immediate
           тНЭ execution works line by line (and parsing the first line would fail).

           тНЭ valid split into several lines (in a defined function)
           тНЭ
           тИЗFOO X
            XтЙе0             тЖТтЖТ
            X 'is positive' тЖРтЖТ
            X 'is negative' тЖРтЖР
           тИЗ
           FOO 5
      5 is positive
           FOO ┬п5
      ┬п5 is negative


           тНЭ invalid split into several lines: тЖРтЖТ spread over 2 lines.
           тНЭ FOO can be properly parsed, but calling FOO fails.
           тНЭ
           тИЗFOO X
           XтЙе0 тЖТтЖТ X 'is positive' тЖР
                тЖТ X 'is negative' тЖРтЖР
           тИЗ
           FOO 5
     SYNTAX ERROR+
     FOO[1]  X 'is positive'тЖР
             *              *

   The recommended usage of the corresponding тЖТтЖТ, тЖРтЖТ, and тЖРтЖР token of
the same conditional is to:

   тАв either put all of them on the same line (short format), or
   тАв else align all of them on the same column (long form), but
   тАв never mix the short and long forms

   In theory one could place (and align) the token before or after their
statement(s).  However, placing them after their statement(s), like
shown in the examples above, makes them arguably more visible and is
therefore the recommended way.  In particular when conditionals are
being nested.


