2.45.3 A Possible Pitfall
-------------------------

In APL, as well as in C/C++ (and most other languages), an expression is
also a statement, but not vice versa.  Expressions yield a value, while
statements may not.

   The C/C++ language knows conditional statements and conditional
expressions:

        if (COND) { IF-statements }       // conditional C/C++ statement
        else      { ELSE-statements }

        (COND) ? IF-value : ELSE-value    // conditional C/C++ expression

   Likewise, GNU APL also has conditional statements and conditional
expressions:

           COND тЖТтЖТ IF-statements тЖРтЖТ ELSE-statements тЖРтЖР    тНЭ conditional APL statement

           IF-value тКв[COND] ELSE-value                    тНЭ conditional APL expression

   If a value is needed, e.g.  for assigning it to a variable, but the
expression becomes too long to fit in a single line, then one can
replicate the assignment in both of the IF and the ELSE clauses:

           // C/C++
           x = -5;
           Result = (x < 0) ? "negative" : "positive";                          // OK
           Result = if (x < 0) { "negative"; } else { "positive"; }         // syntax error
           if (x < 0) { Result = "negative"; } else { Result = "positive"; }   // OK

           тНЭ GNU APL conditional expression, aka. тКв[]
           XтЖР┬п5
           Result тЖР "positive" тКв[X < 0] "negative"                     тНЭ OK
           Result тЖР (X < 0) тЖТтЖТ тКг"negative" тЖРтЖТ тКг"positive" тЖРтЖР           тНЭ ???
           Result
     1

           (X < 0) тЖТтЖТ Result тЖР "negative" тЖРтЖТ Result тЖР "positive" тЖРтЖР    тНЭ OK
           Result
     negative

   The correct, although possibly unexpected, result 1 of the APL
conditional in the line with comment тНЭ ???  above was evaluated as
follows:

  1. APL computes different statements from right to left.
  2. The conditional tokens тЖТтЖТ, тЖРтЖТ, and тЖРтЖР are statement separators like
     тЧК, but with the additional capability to jump over their THEN
     and/or ELSE clauses according to the value of their COND clause.
  3. The first statement in the example above is тАШResult тЖР (X < 0)тАЩ i.e.
     тАШResultтЖР1тАЩ.
  4. The statement result of COND is always a committed value,
     regardless of whether it is assigned to a variable (like in the
     example above) or not.  Therefore the COND clause does not produce
     any output.
  5. The next statement that is being executed it either тАШтКг"negative"тАЩ
     or else тАШтКг"positive"тАЩ, depending on the value of variable X.
     Normally it would be displayed, but due to тКг the display is
     suppressed.  The entire conditional does therefore produce no
     output.
  6. As a consequence, тАШResult тЖР 1тАЩ (and not, for example, тАШ"negative"тАЩ
     !).
  7. The тАШтКг"negative"тАЩ and тАШтКг"positive"тАЩ are separate statements which
     do not assign anything to Result in the previous COND clause.  The
     pitfall in the example is that the conditional looks like it would
     assign either "negative" or "positive" to Result, but in fact
     assigns 1.

   Needless to say that, as in the example above, the assignment of a
APL conditional statement to a variable is, although possible, a dubious
programming style that should be avoided for the sake of readability.
The key takeaway here is that the clauses of a GNU APL conditional are
(two or three) different statements, and that an assignment of the
conditional to a variable assigns only the first of these statements to
the variable.

   In C/C++, the condition of a conditional statement MUST be put in
parentheses, while the condition of a conditional expression MAY be put
in parentheses.

   In GNU APL the condition of a conditional statement MAY be put in
parentheses, while the condition of conditional expression MUST be put
in brackets (since it is the axis argument X of A тКв[X] B.. A good
programming practice in C/C++ and in GNU APL is to always put the
condition into parentheses even if that if not syntactically required.
Some people even use double parentheses to emphasize the condition of a
conditional statement or expression.


