2.46 Matrix Product
===================

In standard APL, the inner product Z of two matrices A and B as known
from linear algebra, is:

           ZтЖРA +.├Ч B      тНЭ the most frequent special case of A f.g B

   However, the inner product in APL is more general than the inner
product in linear algebra.  In the general case A f.g B may the
functions f and g also be non-scalar APL primitives or even defined
functions.  This generality may occasionally be helpful, but it comes
with a performance penalty since many argument checks are duplicated.
At the same time A +.├Ч B is by far the most frequent use of the inner
product operator тАЩ.тАЩ.

   For this reason GNU APL also provides a slightly more efficient
dyadic function тИШ (Matrix Product) for the special case +.├Ч of the
dyadic operator тАЩ.тАЩ.  This function тИШ has been optimized for numeric
arguments and computes the matrix product as known from linear algebra.

   For two-dimensional matrices A and B is function тИШ conceptually the
same as +.├Ч:

   AтИШB тЖРтЖТ A +.├Ч B

   However, there are some subtle differences between the function тИШ and
the operator +.├Ч:

   тАв A +.├Ч B allows A and B to be of any rank, while AтИШB raises a RANK
     ERROR if the rank of A or B is more than 2.

   тАв The product A +.├Ч B can be a vector (e.g.  if A is a vector and B
     is a matrix), usually understood as row-vector.  In contrast (and
     more similar to linear algebra) AтИШB is always a matrix.
   тАв In order to preserve the distinction between row vectors and column
     vectors the arguments A and B of тИШ are possibly reshaped according
     to the following rules:

        тАв if A and/or B is a scalar then the normal (element-wise)
          product of A and B is computed.  That is, AтИШB тЖРтЖТ A├ЧB.
        тАв if A is a APL vector of length N then it is reshaped to a
          row-vector before AтИШB is computed.  In this context, the term
          row-vector shall refer to a matrix of shape (1 N).
        тАв if B is a APL vector of length N then it is reshaped to a
          column-vector before AтИШB is computed.  In this context, the
          term column-vector shall refer to a matrix of shape (N 1).

     Examples:

                MтЖР2 2тН┤1 2 3 4   тНЭ a matrix
                VтЖР10 11         тНЭ a vector

                M +.├Ч V
          32 74

                MтИШV
          32
          74

                V +.├Ч M
          43 64

                VтИШM
          43 64

                тН┤M +.├Ч V   тНЭ the result is an (APL-) vector of length 2
          2
                тН┤V +.├Ч M   тНЭ the result is an (APL-) vector of length 2
          2
                тН┤VтИШM       тНЭ the result is row vector
          1 2
                тН┤MтИШV       тНЭ the result is column vector
          2 1

   тАв A +.├Ч B requires that the number of columns in A is equal to the
     number of rows in B. In contrast, AтИШB has no such requirement and
     will add 0-columns to A resp.  0-rows to B to match the shapes of A
     and B. Naturally, the multiplications of these 0-columns or 0-rows
     is not in fact performed, but optimized away.


