     LO      : Value  11 22 33 lop
     OPER2   : Operator
     RO      : Value  rop
     B       : Value  1 2 3

   The results are rather interesting.  We will later on discuss a
potential difference between vector notation at tokenization time and
vector notation at execution time.  The same outcome of tests 2a.  and
2b.  demonstrates that IBM APL2 handles both variants in the same
fashion (supposedly because both cases are resolved at execution time).

   Test 2a.  proves that vector notation binds stronger than the left
operand to its dyadic operator.  Test 2c.  demonstrates how the binding
strengths can be undermined with parentheses.

   Test 2d.  proves that the right operand binds stronger than vector
notation.  However, this case is interesting from an iso.  Page 126 of
iso gives the following example for the dyadic rank operator:

           тНЭ example from ISO/IEC 13751 p.126
           тНЭ
           0 1 2тМ╜тИШ0 1 'ABC'
     ABC
     BCA
     CAB

   Comparing the results of Test 2d.  with GNU APL shows how iso
believes their example should be parsed:

           тНЭ Test 2e. (GNU APL):
           тНЭ
           0 1 2(тМ╜тНд0 1) 'ABC'
     ABC
     BCA
     CAB

           тНЭ Test 2f. (GNU APL):
           тНЭ
           0 1 2(тМ╜тНд0) 1 'ABC'
     LENGTH ERROR
           0 1 2(тМ╜тНд0 0 0)1 'ABC'
           ^            ^

   NOTE: It is not possible to run tests 2e.  and 2f.  in IBM APL2
directly (because at least in the PC demo version of IBM APL2 the rank
operator тНд is not implemented.  However using our defined function OPER2
above instead of тНд shows that IBM APL2 evaluates the ISO example as 0 1
2(тМ╜тИШ0) 1 тАЩABCтАЩ (in accordance with lrm) and not as 0 1 2(тМ╜тИШ0 1) тАЩABCтАЩ as
iso suggests.

   Takeaways: the tests above teach us the following:

   тАв Vector notation differs between:
        тАв The ISO standard for APL,
        тАв IBM APL2, and
        тАв APL implementation of other vendors (including GNU APL).
   тАв It is therefore impossible to accommodate both the ISO standard and
     IBM APL2 to 100% at the same time, but
   тАв GNU APL tries to be as close as possible to one of them,
   тАв The issues highlighted above can be easily avoided by always using
     parentheses around operators and their operands (even though they
     may appear to be redundant).  These parentheses are the (only) key
     to portable APL programs.


