6 GNU APL Project Structure
***************************

The top-level directory of the GNU APL project has a structure like
this:

         apl-2.0/
         тФЬтФАтФА build
         тФЬтФАтФА debian
         тФЬтФАтФА doc
         тФЬтФАтФА erlang
         тФЬтФАтФА gnu-apl.d
         тФЬтФАтФА HOWTOs
         тФЬтФАтФА html
         тФЬтФАтФА m4
         тФЬтФАтФА rpm
         тФЬтФАтФА src
         тФЬтФАтФА support-files
         тФЬтФАтФА tools
         тФЬтФАтФА websock
         тФЬтФАтФА workspaces
         тФЬтФАтФА wslib2
         тФЬтФАтФА wslib3
         тФЬтФАтФА wslib4
         тФФтФАтФА wslib5

   Most of these directories are contained in the project tar file (e.g.
apl-2.0.tar.gz) and some are created during the build of GNU APL. Only
the directories in the top-level are shown above.

   The GNU APL project follows the standard layout for autoconf/automake
projects.  The top-level itself contains the files needed by
autoconf/automake and a handful of README-XXX files that might be of
interest when building GNU APL.

   The sub-directories are (in order of decreasing relevance):

* Menu:

* The sub-directory src::
* The sub-directory support-files::
* The sub-directory doc::
* The sub-directory HOWTOs::
* The sub-directories workspaces and wslib2 ... wslib5::
* The sub-directory m4::
* The sub-directories debian and debian_tmp::
* The sub-directory tools::


File: apl.info,  Node: The sub-directory src,  Next: The sub-directory support-files,  Up: GNU APL Project Structure

6.1 The sub-directory src
=========================

The sub-directory src contains all C++ source files that are needed to
build either the GNU APL interpreter itself, or libapl (a library that
contains the essential part of GNU APL, but without the interactive REPL
loop of the interpreter).  During the build, the object files produced
by the compiler are also placed in this directory.

   The sub-directory src contains further sub-directories for components
of GNU APL that are optional and typically require the installation of
additional libraries on the build machine.  The ./configure script in
the top-level directory determines, which optional components shall be
included in the build.

         apl-2.0/
         тФЬтФАтФА src
          ┬а┬а тФЬтФАтФА APs                     APs for тОХSVO and friends
          ┬а┬а тФЬтФАтФА emacs_mode              dito
          ┬а┬а тФЬтФАтФА Gtk                     тОХGTK (graphical user interface)
          ┬а┬а тФЬтФАтФА native                  templates for native functions
          ┬а┬а тФЬтФАтФА sql                     тОХSQL
          ┬а┬а тФЬтФАтФА testcases               dito

   GNU APL comes with an automated test suite, the testcases are
contained in sub-directory src/testcases


File: apl.info,  Node: The sub-directory support-files,  Next: The sub-directory doc,  Prev: The sub-directory src,  Up: GNU APL Project Structure

6.2 The sub-directory support-files
===================================

The sub-directory support-file contains a number of configuration files
that aim at making a standard keyboard produce APL characters.  Details
are explained in top-level file README-3-keyboard.


File: apl.info,  Node: The sub-directory doc,  Next: The sub-directory HOWTOs,  Prev: The sub-directory support-files,  Up: GNU APL Project Structure

6.3 The sub-directory doc
=========================

The sub-directory doc is used to create this info file in different file
formats (.info, .html).


File: apl.info,  Node: The sub-directory HOWTOs,  Next: The sub-directories workspaces and wslib2 ... wslib5,  Prev: The sub-directory doc,  Up: GNU APL Project Structure

6.4 The sub-directory HOWTOs
============================

The sub-directory HOWTOs contains some documents that try to explain how
some of the non-standard features of GNU APL are intended to be used.
These documents were written for two different audiences: APL
programmers and GNU APL hackers.  The documents for APL programmers are,
by default, installed in directory /usr/local/share/doc/apl by make
install while the documents for GNU APL hackers (i.e.  C++ programmers
or trouble-shooters) are not installed by make install, but rather
remain in the source tree.


File: apl.info,  Node: The sub-directories workspaces and wslib2 ... wslib5,  Next: The sub-directory m4,  Prev: The sub-directory HOWTOs,  Up: GNU APL Project Structure

6.5 The sub-directories workspaces and wslib2 ... wslib5
========================================================

These directories (and their content) are, by default, copied to
/usr/local/lib/apl by make install.  Some sub-directories are empty
while others contain small workspaces or libraries for various purposes
(mostly demonstrating the use of some non-standard APL features).


File: apl.info,  Node: The sub-directory m4,  Next: The sub-directories debian and debian_tmp,  Prev: The sub-directories workspaces and wslib2 ... wslib5,  Up: GNU APL Project Structure

6.6 The sub-directory m4
========================

The sub-directory m4 contains macros used by autoconf and automake.  In
most cases the top-level ./configure script can be used as is.  If a
platform on which GNU APL shall be built differs too much from the
platform on which the GNU APL project tar file (e.g.  apl-2.0.tar.gz)
was created, then it might be necessary to re-create the ./configure
script on the platform.

   Re-creating the ./configure script requires:

   тАв the installation of autoconf,
   тАв the installation of automake,
   тАв the installation of libtool,
   тАв maybe running aclocal, libtoolize, and other scripts, and finally
   тАв running autoreconf


File: apl.info,  Node: The sub-directories debian and debian_tmp,  Next: The sub-directory tools,  Prev: The sub-directory m4,  Up: GNU APL Project Structure

6.7 The sub-directories debian and debian_tmp
=============================================

These sub-directories are templates for building Debian packages that
contain GNU APL. Sub-directory debian_tmp is initially empty and acts as
a scratch directory inside which the interpreter is being compiled when
a Debian package is built.


File: apl.info,  Node: The sub-directory tools,  Prev: The sub-directories debian and debian_tmp,  Up: GNU APL Project Structure

6.8 The sub-directory tools
===========================

GNU APL uses generated C++ code.  The sub-directory tools contains the
source code for the code generator (phrase_gen) and also some other
small tools for various purposes.  These tools are typically used by GNU
APL hackers and are therefore not installed by make install.


